<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Does More to Relieve Japanese Crisis: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
done more than its share to help relieve the financial and
economic crises in Japan and Asia, said a senior European
Commission official Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Leon Brittan, vice-president of the commission, the executive
body of the 15-nation EU, told visiting Japanese International
Trade and Industry Minister Kaoru Yosano that the EU had done a
lot in absorbing Japan's exports to accelerate the economic
recovery in both Japan and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports to the EU rose 19 percent last year with its
imports from the EU down five percent, said Leon Brittan, adding
that Japanese exports to the United States went up 11 percent at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Kaoru Yosano said Tokyo doesn't want to shift i
ts economic difficulties onto someone else and has been working
to boost domestic demands instead.
</P>
<P>
In response to Japan's demand for 50 deregulation measures
being carried out by the EU, the EU required Thursday that about
200 appropriate measures be taken by Japan to stimulate economic
recovery and to improve market access in the country.
</P>
<P>
Both the officials agreed that these measures will play a
vital role in stimulating economic growth and improving market
access. They welcomed the steps taken by the business circles of
the two sides to resolve key issues of mutual concern and to
expand EU-Japan relationship.
</P>
<P>
Brittan and Yosano shared the view that the EU and Japan, as
two of the major economies in the world, shoulder a joint
responsibility to ensure global economic stability and growth.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the sound macroeconomics policy and structural
reforms, the newly-launched single currency will help create
stability in the world financial market and advance international
trade, they stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese minister brushed aside a reported proposal on
freezing the exchange rates between the main currencies, noting
that the rates should reflect basic economic principles and real
financial situation and it isn't advisable to freeze them.
</P>
<P>
"Fluctuation is only natural," he voiced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
