<HEADLINE> Williams, Kournikova into HK Int'l Tennis Semi-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian teenager sensation
Anna Kournikova and American Serena Williams qualified for the
singles semi-finals after winning their first round matches at the
inaugural Super-Power Challenge Cup women's tennis tournament here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kournikova, third seed of the three-day exhibition tournament,
beat Chinese ace Li Fang 6-1, 6-4 in 56 minutes while
fourth-seeded Serena Williams downed Thailand's 37th-ranked
Tamarine Tanasugarn 6-2, 6-1 in 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
With a tricky and flexible game, 17-year-old Kournikova took
the upper hand in the first set, breaking all of Li's four games
while having only one of her own games broken.
</P>
<P>
Li came back strongly after losing the three games in the
second set, winning two games in a row with her serve-and-volley
play and, after two more games lost, leveled the game score at
four-all.
</P>
<P>
But the 17-year-old Russian played a suprisingly controled game
to force her Chinese opponent into many unforced errors and won
two more games to take the match.
</P>
<P>
Kournikova will face second-seeded American Venus Williams,
elder sister of Serena Williams, while Serena Williams will take
on top seed and former world number one Steffi Graf from Germany,
in the semi-finals on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I played very well today and I'm quite satisfied for my first
match of the year," said Kournikova, a Moscow-born part-time
model.
</P>
<P>
She said she would continue to try different kind of play in
the future as she did in the second set in Thursday's match.
</P>
<P>
"I can not change the way of play of others but I can control
my own way of play," she said.
</P>
<P>
Kournikova, whose world ranking had risen from 224th in 1995 to
13th at the end of last year, admitted that she still needed
experience to deal with tough matches and to learn how to build up
strong nerves.
</P>
<P>
Serena Williams had no problems beating Thailand's Asian Games
silver-medalist Tanasugarn, with her superb play. The lob-sided
match saw six double faults from the 37th-ranked Thai and five
Aces by Williams.
</P>
<P>
Graf and Venus Williams had been given semi-final spots due to
byes for them at the first round on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ranked No. 1 in the world for a record length of 377
consecutive weeks, the German ace had long suffered from sustained
injuries, which had brought her ranking down. But she still ranked
ninth at the year-ending world rankings for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Venus Williams, 18, had brought her world ranking from 211st at
early 1997 up to fifth at the year-ending rankings for 1998.
</P>
<P>
In the doubles first round which was also semi-finals on
Thursday, top-seeded duo Li Fang and Serena Williams downed their
opponents Venus Williams and Lin Ning from Hong Kong SAR 7-6
(7-2), 3-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
In the final on Saturday, Li and Venus Williams will meet the
winners of another semi-final match on Friday, between Steffi
Graf/Tong Ka Po and Kournikova/Tanasugarn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
