<HEADLINE> Euro Continues to Fall Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The euro continued to fall against
the dollar and the European Central Bank announced a reference
rate for Thursday of 1.1632 dollars, more than a cent lower than
the 1.1743 dollars on the previous day.
</P>
<P>
The euro fell against other currencies too, with rates set at
0.70585 pounds after 0.70760 pounds and 129.43 yen after 131.42
yen Wednesday. But the euro was up against the Swiss franc at
1.6165 after 1.6116 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
German shares retreated on the Frankfurt Stock Exchange
Thursday after an early rally, trimming the main market index, the
DAX, to 5,316.58 at 2 p.m., a fall of 127.04 points compared to
Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
Europe's other markets were also soft Thursday. By
mid-afternoon the FT 100 in London was down 73.09 points to
6,074.90. Vienna prices were down a minimal 0.2 percent, but
Amsterdam stocks fell a painful 4 percent across the board.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, auto stocks, the power shares on the previous day,
were among the big bugaboos for German investors, with the BMW
stock off 28 euros at settlement to 714.00 euros. Volkswagen was
down 3.10 euros to 75.50. 
</P>
</TEXT>
