<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Britain Sign Intent on Industrial Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Britain Thursday
signed a declaration of intent on industrial cooperation based on South
Africa's defense equipment procurement package.
</P>
<P>
The six-point declaration was signed by visiting British Prime Minister
Tony Blair and South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to hold regular meetings between foreign trade
and defense authorities to monitor, report and oversee Britain's counter-
trade commitments to South Africa as a result of military equipment sales
to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Britain, in consultation with the South African side, would send an
official to the South African Department of Trade and Industry to oversee
the counter-trade arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to "work together for mutual benefit,
seeking wherever possible to maximize the socio-economic benefits arising
from defense procurement."
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration, the British Department of Trade and
Industry and the Ministry of Defense will enter discussions with the South
African negotiation team to explore coordination of the finance
arrangements for the arms deal between the successful bidders for the
defense equipment contracts from Britain, Germany, Sweden and Italy.
</P>
<P>
South African cabinet in November approved a 30-billion-Rand (5.2-
billion-U.S. Dollar) arms deal and announced preferred suppliers for the
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Britain won contracts for maritime helicopters and trainer jets. Twenty-
eight Gripen fighter jets, jointly made by Sweden's Saab and British
Aerospace, were also included in the package.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
