<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French President Proposes Limited Currency Fluctuation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
proposed Thursday that the Group of Seven (G-7) most
industrialized nations work together to limit the fluctuations
between the U.S. dollar, the euro and the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"Greater exchange rate stability is necessary," said Chirac
after meeting with visiting Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
"The coming of the euro offers the opportunity for real concert
within the G-7 to reduce fluctuations between the dollar, the euro
and the yen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, who is the first Japanese prime minister to visit
Europe since 1995, said during a meeting with French entrepreneurs
Thursday, "A three-way cooperation between Japan, Europe and the
United States would enable us to create a stable, developed
international monetary system."
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that the euro will help the world maintain a better
balance in the financial system in the process of globalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
