<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-07 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Oil Minister on Oil-for-Food Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has signed 42 oil
contracts since the fifth phase of the U.N. oil-for-food program
started on November 26 last year, said Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Mohammed Rashid Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Economist weekly, Rashid said 30
contracts have got approval from the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was put under the U.N. sanctions after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990, but in 1996 the U.N. hammered out an oil-for-food
program allowing Iraq to export a limited amount of oil to buy
food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Under the six-month fifth phase, Iraq is allowed to export 5.2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said the approved contracts have been implemented since
early last month and Iraqi oil were shipped to world market via
Iraq's oil terminal of al-Bakr and the Turkish port of Ceyhan.
</P>
<P>
He added Iraq will market 300 million barrels of crude oil
during the fifth phase.
</P>
<P>
On oil cooperation with Jordan, Rashid said the two countries
will start this week to study Jordan's need for oil in 1999 based
on an agreement signed last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which should be renewed every year, Iraq
provided Jordan with 4.8 million tonnes of crude oil and refined
oil products in 1998 at preferential prices.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said a Jordanian delegation headed by Minister of Energy
Hani Malki will visit Iraq shortly to renew the oil agreement.
</P>
<P>
He also said the construction of the 750-kilometer-long oil
pipeline linking Haditha in northwestern Iraq and the Jordanian
oil refinery of al-Zarqa will start soon.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline, with an investment of 300 million U.S. dollars,
has a transfer capacity of 150,000 barrels per day when going into
operation.
</P>
<P>
As for the Iraqi-Syrian oil pipeline, Rashid said talks to
reopen the pipeline are still underway and part of the oil spare
parts needed for restoration have been secured.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi-Syrian pipeline was closed in 1982 during the
eight-year Iraq-Iran war, in which Syria sided with Iran.
</P>
<P>
In July 1988, Iraq and Syria agreed to reopen the pipeline
which carries crude oil from the Iraqi northern city of Kirkuk to
the export terminal in the Syrian port city of Banias on the
Mediterranean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
