<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Achebe Named Goodwill Ambassador for U.N. Population Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA) Thursday announced the appointment of
renowned Nigerian author, Chinua Achebe, as a goodwill ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Achebe is regarded by many as the "father of the modern African
novel." His books "Things Fall Apart" (1958) and "No Longer at
Ease" (1960) marked a new era in African writing and sold millions
of copies around the world.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted to have been appointed goodwill ambassador for
the Population Fund," Achebe told a press conference here. "I am a
strong supporter of the United Nations and its agencies and of the
work of the Population Fund in reproductive health and gender
equity."
</P>
<P>
"I think we who are comfortable often take things like health
care and family planning for granted and we forget about the
people who are in difficulty, they seem rather remote, but that
shouldn't be so. It is those who have difficult lives that we
should be concerned about," he said.
</P>
<P>
Achebe, who was born in 1930 in Nigeria, is currently Charles
Setevenson Professor of Literature at Bard College,
Annandale-on-Hudson, New York.
</P>
<P>
"We are honored to have Mr. Achebe as a goodwill ambassador
for the Population Fund," said Dr. Nafis Sadik, executive
director of UNFPA. "His standing as a legend of African writing
makes him a wonderful representative for the work of the fund,
especially in Africa."
</P>
<P>
"We look forward very much to working with him to promote the
responsibilities and rights of men and women everywhere in
regard to reproductive health care," the executive director said.
</P>
<P>
As a goodwill ambassador, Achebe will represent the fund at a
number of events taking place this year: These include the June
30-July 2 United Nations General Assembly special session, which
will review progress in the five years since the International
Conference on Population and Development, and the Day of Six
Billion on October 12, marking the growth of the world population
to more than 6 billion.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Population Fund is the world's largest
multilateral source of population assistance. Over the past 30
years, the fund has provided 4.3 billion U.S. dollars in
assistance to more than 160 countries. The fund's priority program
areas are reproductive health, population and development
strategies, and advocacy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
