<HEADLINE> More Congo (K) Refugees Pouring into Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 7 (Xinhua) - Though a cease-fire summit by
conflicting parties in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is scheduled
late
this month, the DRC refugees are still pouring into western Tanzania over
the past few days, an official statement said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 645 DRC refugees have been received in Kigoma region between
November 23 last year and January 3 this year, the statement from the
Ministry of Home Affairs said.
</P>
<P>
"The latest flow of refugees from the DRC was on January 5 when 161
refugees were received at Kigoma by the United Nations High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR)," it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 110 refugees from Burundi have been received by UNHCR at
Kigoma during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the UNHCR planned a census of all refugees in Kigoma camps
this month to get a clear base of refugee statistics and curb dual
registration.
</P>
<P>
In a late last November statement, the Home Affairs Ministry said a
total of some 20,000 refugees from the DRC and Burundi had entered the
Kigoma Region since a bloody crisis broke out in DRC early August, bringing
the grand total to 236,425.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese refugees include those who had been repatriated
voluntarily from Kigoma camps under an exercise which was however halted in
August 8 following the emergence of new fighting in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
By the time the voluntary repatriation of Congolese refugees came to a
halt, 27,075 refugees had been repatriated.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese refugees are fleeing battles taking place in the eastern
part of their country between DRC government forces loyal to President
Laurent Kabila and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Claiming to be neutral in the DRC conflict, Tanzania recalled its
military advisors from DRC almost immediately after the conflict broke out
while other neighboring countries rushed their troops to either side of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The war has so far already drawn in Angola, Namibia, Chad, Libya, Sudan
and Zimbabwe on Kabila's side while the Tutsi-led rebels are backed by
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Chief of Tanzania Defense Forces, General
Robert Mboma, arrived in Kigoma Wednesday on a three-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
He had met local defense and security officials and was expected to
inspect the Tanzania-Burundi border at Mnanila Manyovu in Kasulu District.
</P>
</TEXT>
