<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Six Basic Questions on UNFPA Goodwill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA) Thursday named Chinua Achebe, renowned
Nigerian author, a goodwill ambassador. Following are six basic
questions on the UNFPA goodwill ambassador:
</P>
<P>
1. Who were appointed goodwill ambassadors before Achebe?
</P>
<P>
The UNFPA named six persons as Goodwill Ambassador in October
1998. They are:
</P>
<P>
a) Ted Turner, U.S., businessman, philanthropist and founder of
the Turner Foundation which supports environmental and population
projects;
</P>
<P>
b) Jane Fonda, U.S., actress, community activist, and
well-known advocate for the environment and human rights;
</P>
<P>
c) Keiko Kishi, prominent Japanese movie and stage actress and
an accomplished writer;
</P>
<P>
d) Manisha Koirala, India, film actress;
</P>
<P>
e) Safia El-Emary, Egypt, actress;
</P>
<P>
f) Jamal Soliman, Syria, expert on theater arts,
</P>
<P>
2. What are the qualities needed to be a UNFPA goodwill
ambassador?
</P>
<P>
-- Goodwill ambassador should have a strong and expressed
interest in reproductive health care and in the status of women;
</P>
<P>
-- An ambassador should command national or international media
attention or work with the media;
</P>
<P>
-- An ambassador should have a demonstrated interest in human
rights and developing countries and peoples;
</P>
<P>
-- An ambassador should be prepared to take on the duties of an
ambassador, listed below.
</P>
<P>
An ambassador may have a relevant personal story and can serve
as a symbol to generate support for specific programs, e.g.,
against harmful traditional practices.
</P>
<P>
3. What are the duties of a UNFPA goodwill ambassador?
</P>
<P>
-- Visit UNFPA, IPPF and NGO reproductive health care and
family planning projects in developing countries to give
encouragement to and focus attention on those programs;
</P>
<P>
-- In developed countries, discuss the needs of reproductive
health care and family planning programs in developing countries,
citing the work of the projects visited;
</P>
<P>
-- Make public appearances, make public service announcements
and video news releases, participate in press conferences as well
as electronic and print interviews;
</P>
<P>
-- Participate in major, national UNFPA campaign activities,
e.g., the Face to Face campaign. Testify (if willing and
interested in doing so) in front of governmental officials and
other social and economic or development policy decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
4. How is a UNFPA goodwill ambassador chosen?
</P>
<P>
-- An ambassador must possess some or all of the qualities
listed above;
</P>
<P>
-- Contact between a potential ambassador and the UNFPA may be
initiated by the UNFPA directly by a partner NGO in a particular
country,
</P>
<P>
-- Once a celebrity has agreed to be a UNFPA goodwill
ambassador and the UNFPA is satisfied that they have the necessary
qualities to be a goodwill ambassador, the appointment is
announced by Dr. Nafis Sadik, executive director of the UNFPA.
</P>
<P>
5. What are the goals of a UNFPA goodwill ambassador?
</P>
<P>
-- To bring to the attention of the public and decision-makers
throughout the world the needs of people in the developing world,
especially for reproductive health care, including family
planning, sexual health and reproductive rights;
</P>
<P>
-- To remind donor governments of the promises they made in
Cairo in 1994 at the International Conference on Population and
Development (ICPD) to increase their financial contributions so
that the ICPD Program of Action can be fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
6. Are the UNFPA campaigns aimed at ordinary people?
</P>
<P>
-- Many people around the world recognize the right of all
women having access to reproductive health care, family planning
information and services, and reproductive rights. However, a
larger number of the same people are unaware of how many women do
not enjoy these rights and do not have access to these services;
how many women die daily because of a lack of these services; and
what mechanisms exist to help establish and guarantee reproductive
rights and deliver reproductive health care and family planning
services;
</P>
<P>
-- The UNFPA's awareness campaigns, such as the Face to Face
campaign, are designed to (1) bring these facts to the attention
of the public; (2) encourage people to participate in campaigns
through direct participation or advocacy activities; and (3)
create a constituency knowledgeable on these issues and support of
their governments international assistance commitments, especially
in the area of reproductive health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
