<HEADLINE> Greece Supports S-300 Missiles Deployment in Crete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece stressed Thursday that
both Athens and Nicosia supported the idea of installing the
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in the southern Greek
island of Crete instead of Cyprus itself.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas said that this was the will of both the Greek and
Cypriot governments and would be implemented.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Cypriot government was now in contact with
Russia regarding issues related to the missiles.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen its defense, Cyprus decided earlier last year to
purchase and deploy the Russian missiles on the divided island,
but neighboring Turkey has threatened to use force to prevent the
missile deployment.
</P>
<P>
After consultations with Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis in
December, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides announced in Nicosia
the cancellation of plans to install the missiles in Cyprus and
the start of negotiations with Moscow their possible deployment in
Crete.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Cyprus signed a joint defense pact in 1993, under
which Athens is bound to defend Nicosia in the event of renewed
hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on this, Reppas said that Athens stood firmly at the
side of Nicosia and would not do anything to jeopardize the strong
unity between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
