<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair, Mandela Report Progress on Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela and British Prime Minister Tony Blair Thursday reported progress in
talks about the pending trial of two Libyans suspected of involvement in
the 1988 Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
After meeting at Mandela's Pretoria residence, the two leaders told
reporters that they had made headway on the outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Blair declined to reveal details of their discussions.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very sensitive matter which involves three different
governments -- Libya, Britain and the United States," Mandela was quoted by
South African Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It will be improper for us to go into any details in regard to this
discussion except to say that we have made good progress and we think that
we are on the way to resolve all the outstanding issues."
</P>
<P>
Mandela announced that Jakes Gerwel, director-general in the president's
office, and Prince Bander, Saudi Arabian Ambassador to Washington, would
meet Libyan President Muammar Qaddafi in a matter of days to brief him on
Thursday's talks.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked the United Nations Security Council for allowing the
two delegates to fly straight to Libya despite U.N. imposed sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he and Mandela had made a lot of progress on the matter,
which he said many people believed could never be resolved.
</P>
<P>
"We have come a long way and we will carry on doing everything we
possibly can in order to make that progress," said the British prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
"We will do that not just for reasons of political relations between
countries, but also for people in my country out of a deep sense of respect
for the families of the Lockerbie victims and their desire for this trial
to happen and some light to be shed on what actually took place."
</P>
<P>
A bomb exploded on a U.S.-bound Pan Am airliner over the Scottish
town of Lockerbie on December 21, 1988, killing 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Libya has recently agreed with Britain and the U.S. that the two
Libyans stand trial in the Netherlands, but the trial still stalls as the
two sides could not agree on outstanding issues like where the two should
complete their sentences if convicted.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the recent U.S. and British bombings of Iraq, Mandela said: "
There is no issue which cannot be settled."
</P>
<P>
He said he had no doubt that Blair and U.S. President Bill Clinton
respected a U.N. resolution that its member countries should resolve their
problems through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that in due course the parties concerned will be able, using
the United Nations, to sit down and resolve this matter. That is how we
have solved some of the most intractable problems in our country."
</P>
<P>
Asked if he had tried to persuade Blair to drop Britain's bid to host
the 2006 soccer world cup, Mandela said he had forgotten and jokingly asked
the visitor: "Will you be generous enough to do this?"
</P>
<P>
Blair replied: "Friendly rivalry is always a good thing."
</P>
<P>
Blair paid tribute to Mandela, who is set to retire after this year's
general election.
</P>
<P>
"He has been throughout his entire life a shining light, and I don't
think that light will ever be dimmed," said Blair.
</P>
<P>
He described Mandela as a man of compassion, commitment, integrity,
strength and forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
Mandela quipped: "He is nice to an old man because he realizes that I
am no threat to him any longer." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
