<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-07 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Defies U.S. Criticism Over Wye Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 7 (Xinhua) - Israel Thursday refuted a blame
that the U.S. laid on it for the impasse in the Wye peace accord,
vowing not to transfer more land in the West Bank to the
Palestinians until they have fulfilled their obligations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians should not look to Washington for help in
order to have Israel transfer more land, but should honor their
commitments under the Wye agreement instead, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. administration took the Israeli government to task
Wednesday, disputing an article written by Israeli Ambassador
Zalman Shoval and published in the Washington Times in which he
pins blame on the Palestinians for the stalemate in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
In the article, Shoval insisted that Israel give no more land
to the Palestinians because they have failed to fulfill their
obligations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said Wednesday the
Palestinians have in fact worked hard to implement their
commitments under the Wye agreement, including annulling
anti-Israel clauses in the Palestinian charter and stepping up the
fight against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"There are some commitments that still have to be fulfilled,
but overall they are making progress," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He also said "the Israelis have not yet fulfilled their
obligations", referring to the phased Israeli troop withdrawals
from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to cobble his coalition cracking over the
Washington-brokered peace deal signed last October, Netanyahu
froze the implementation of the deal soon after Israel carried out
the first phase of the three-stage troop withdrawals in November,
citing alleged Palestinian violations.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Netanyahu, said it is
"peculiar" for Washington to demand that Israel overlook
Palestinian non-compliance and go ahead with the troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
He denied the early elections in May is behind the suspension
of the agreement, echoing Shoval's position that the Palestinians
should take more measures, including collecting illegal weapons
and halting incitement against Israel before Israel carries out
the pending withdrawals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
