<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Financiers Agree to Police Derivatives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A number of the world's largest
financial institutions have reached an agreement to police the
huge and volatile market of derivatives.
</P>
<P>
Top executives from 12 leading institutions in the United
States and other countries agreed at a meeting here Wednesday to
form a new group for setting guidelines, governing trading
practices, lending standards and disclosure requirement, the New
York Times said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, Chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission Arthur Levitt and other senior
officials also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came after the near-collapse last September of
Long-Term Capital Management, the huge hedge fund, which had
invested heavily in derivatives. The financial industry had an
early attempt to control the derivatives market by setting its own
voluntary guidelines but got only a limited success.
</P>
<P>
The Long Term Capital, which borrowed heavily, was rescued by
the intervention of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York last year
when it threatened to wreak havoc on the financial market.
</P>
<P>
The co-chairmen of the industry group are Gerald Corrigan, the
former president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York who is
now a senior executive at Goldman, Sachs, and Stephen Thieke, a
top official at J.P. Morgan. The other members of the group are
Barclays, Bear Stearns, Chase, Citigroup, Credit Suisse, Deutsche
Bank, Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
and UBS.
</P>
<P>
The derivatives market has boomed over the last decade to
become one of the most lucrative activities on Wall Street. About
37 trillion U.S. dollars worth of privately traded derivatives
contracts are outstanding, up from 865 billion U.S. dollars in
1987. However, the figures represent the paper value of all of the
underlying financial products used to create a derivatives
contract. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
