<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Stop to Outside Support for Sierra Leone Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States is pressing
the Liberian government to stop rebels in Sierra Leone from
receiving support through Liberian territory, a State Department
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government is especially concerned about external
regional support for the RUF (Revolutionary United Front)
insurgency," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The official could not say if the U.S. government had evidence
that support for the RUF rebels was coming directly from Liberian
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the rebels had penetrated the Sierra Leone capital
Freetown and were fighting the Western African peacekeeping force
ECOMOG for control of the city. Sporadic shooting erupted
overnight in the east of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The United States suspended operations at its embassy in
Freetown on December 24 and encouraged Americans to leave.
</P>
<P>
"We're not sure how many Americans chose to remain in Sierra
Leone. We believe the number to be small. There were only 120
Americans registered with our embassy and they were notified of
our decision to send operations," State Department spokesman
James Rubin said Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
