<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Dismisses Turkey for FIR Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece Thursday criticized
neighboring Turkey for the latter's attack on Athens regarding the
issue of Athens Flight Information Region (FIR).
</P>
<P>
Greece said that Turkey's aim was to change the status quo of
air traffic control in the Aegean Sea and to create problems in
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey said Tuesday that Greece had been unable to fulfill its
technical duties in the Athens FIR since the 1980s. The Athens
FIR, which Greece has run since 1952, comprises Greek and
international airspace.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Turkish statement, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas described the Turkish claims as "unfounded" and
"full of inaccuracies."
</P>
<P>
He accused Ankara of distorting reality in its attempt to turn
a purely technical issue into a political one.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Reppas said that a new technologically
advanced air traffic control system would become operational next
month, which would provide two-fold coverage and consequently
greater flight safety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
