<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Not Sure to Seek Permanent UN Security Council Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is still considering
whether or not to put itself forward as a candidate for a permanent seat on
the United Nations Security Council, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said in
Pretoria Thursday.
</P>
<P>
There are a number of issues to be resolved first, Mbeki told reporters
after chairing a session of Britain-South Africa Bilateral Forum with
visiting British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said that questions, like whether only one African country should
have permanent status, have not been sorted out. "They don't just affect
the African continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral forum also discussed the situation in Iraq. South Africa
and Britain agreed that Iraq should comply with U.N. Security Council
resolutions on international weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Blair told reporters that Iraq would only become part of the community
of world nations by complying with these resolutions.
</P>
<P>
On the Angolan civil war, Mbeki said South Africa and Britain supported
the Security Council position that the world body should engage the warring
parties in talks in a search for a political solution.
</P>
<P>
Blair pledged that his country would do everything it could to promote
stability and negotiation between the two conflicting parties.
</P>
<P>
The war between the Angolan government troops and the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has been going on since late
1970s.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process went into stalemate because the UNITA did not
comply with the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol aiming to achieve final peace in
the war-torn country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
