<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Officials in charge of Gulf employment firms have
disclosed that employment markets in the Gulf will witness serious
pressures in 1999 due to the inappropriate economic conditions
resulting from the drop in oil prices and the aftermath of the
Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a study printed in Friday's issue of the "Gulf Business"
weekly, the officials said there are growing indications that the
escalating trend of salaries and wages in private companies in the
Gulf might have already reached its peak in 1998.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Financial information printed in Friday's Saudi press
reveals that Saudi share market during the first week of 1999
registered a hike in prices of circulating shares, prompting a
rise in market index to 145.13 points as compared to 141.31 points
on Thursday last week, an increase of 3.82 points or 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The National Bank of Abu Dhabi index of the United
Arab Emirates climbed by 228.57 points during the first week of
1999 to reach 3,814.09 points, an increase of 6.37 percent.
</P>
<P>
Friday's "Al Hayat" daily quoted Ziyad Al Dabbas, director of
the bank's local shares department, as saying the hike in the
index was an outcome of the recovery of local share market demand,
which, in turn, led to a big rise in share prices of local
companies and banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
