<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Pharmaceutical Company Donates Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The famous French
pharmaceutical company Rhone-Poulenc Rorer (RPR) donated medical
products valued at one million yuan to the China Rheumatology
Association today.
</P>
<P>
RPR Marketing Director Jean Marc Barial noted that the
products are used by millions of people around the world, with
international sales ranking 3rd in terms of similar products.
</P>
<P>
The donated pharmaceuticals will be distributed to hospitals
in 11 provinces and prescription sales will be available by the
end of January.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey revealed a high prevalence of rheumatic
diseases in China, with some 18 percent of Chinese citizens
suffering from arthritis. The donated medicine will be used to
treat an estimated 10,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
Oruvail and Profenid are anti-inflamatory agents with no side
effects and significantly greater efficacy than older medicines
such as aspirin. One Oruvail capsule replaces 16 aspirins.
</P>
<P>
Two RPR joint ventures in China will commence production of
Oruvail and Profenid at the end of 1999. However, China will
continue to import the products until the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
RPR is a global pharmaceutical subsidiary of Rhone-Poulenc
S.A., and a new company known as Aventis which will be
incorporated in France to replace the former is expected to
become the world's second largest pharmaceutical company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
