<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Serious Security Problems in Macao Add </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A series of violent crimes taking
place here over the past few days of the new year have aroused
more concern about public security.
</P>
<P>
In addition to looting and kidnapping, there were five
gun-related violent crimes this year, which left one dead and
five injured. In two separate incidents, the manager of a
gambling hall was shot and killed and a prison warden was
seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Many of the crimes were believed to be committed by underworld
gang members.
</P>
<P>
In response to the series of violent incidents, Manuel Soares
Monge, secretary for security of the Macao government, said that
certain evil forces were challenging the society, and that police
forces in Macao would take effective measures to strengthen
investigations and prevent organized crimes.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Silveira, secretary for justice, also voiced his concern
over the series of gun-related crimes at the very beginning of
the year, saying that "Macao faces a difficult year in terms of
public security conditions."
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the judicial forces in his charge will exert
utmost efforts to back public security police in cracking down on
criminal cases and hunting principals.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Chinese government has been paying
close attention to the public security conditions in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Chen Ziying, vice-director of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs
Office under China's State Council, said earlier this week that
the Portuguese Macao government should take practical
responsibility for improving public security in the final year of
Macao's transitional period so that a smooth handover can be
achieved.
</P>
<P>
Chen reiterated that "the Chinese side will abide by the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration and give full support to help
maintain Macao's social stability and economic growth."
</P>
<P>
Zhu Bangzao, spokesman for China's Ministry of Foreign
Affairs, said at a regular press conference Thursday that "the
Portuguese Macao government is responsible for public security in
Macao and maintaining social stability in Macao's
late-transitional period."
</P>
<P>
"In the meantime, the Chinese side is ready to offer help and
cooperation within our power," he said.
</P>
<P>
The crimes have also stirred new anxiety among local
residents, who pointed out that poor public security has affected
the local economy and the daily life of the residents to great
extent, expressing the wish that senior police officers would
boost the morale of police forces and crack down on major
criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
In view of the deteriorating public security, police forces
have intensified crackdown on underworld gang activities. On
Thursday afternoon, Macao police arrested a 35-year-old man, who
is believed to be a ringleader of 14K, an organized gang in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Portugal has offered a helping hand, too. A third group of
about 10 Portuguese police officers came to Macao on Tuesday, and
is expected to help improve the security conditions in Macao. In
August and October of last year, two groups of police officers
had been sent to work here.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning, the new building of Macao's task force
police was put into official use. Meanwhile, the task force
police have been reorganized to include a special mission team, a
bomb-dismantling team and a team using police dogs.
</P>
<P>
Following the reorganization, task force policemen will be
crack members of Macao's police forces and will perform their
duties more effectively in keeping public order and intensify the
crackdown on violent crimes, a senior officer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
