<HEADLINE> Malaysian Ruling Party Postpones Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's largest ruling
party United Malays National Organization (UMNO) Friday decided to
postponed its elections, scheduled for June this year.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached at the UMNO Supreme Council meeting
here Friday, UMNO President Mahathir Mohamad, who is prime
minister, told a press conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Under the party's constitution, the Supreme Council elections
could be postponed up to 18 months from the date of the party's
general assembly which is scheduled in June this year.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the decision also meant that the post of UMNO
deputy president will not be filled until the Supreme Council
elections expected in the 18 months time.
</P>
<P>
The UMNO deputy president's post was left vacant following the
party's former deputy president Anwar Ibrahim's expulsion from the
party on September 4 last year.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the decision to postpone the Supreme Council
elections was to enable UMNO to focus on preparations for the
coming general elections "which have to be held not later than
April 2000".
</P>
<P>
The UMNO Supreme Council elections, held every three years, is
to elect new party president, deputy president and three
vice-presidents as well as 25 Supreme Council members.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the Supreme Council members were also unanimous
in their decision for the post of the deputy prime minister to be
filled now.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir announced after Friday's UMNO Supreme Council meeting
the appointment of Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi as
UMNO's new deputy prime minister.
</P>
<P>
UMNO is the backbone component of the ruling 14-party coalition
National Front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
