<HEADLINE> UAE to Hold Global Environmental Conference in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The new millennium's first
global environmental meeting will be held in Abu Dhabi in the
year 2001, the Gulf News daily reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates (UAE), in cooperation with the United
Nations Environmental Program (UNEP) and other international
organizations, will be organizing the global meeting.
</P>
<P>
The four-day event, entitled "Environment 2001 Conference and
Exhibition," will be held on February 4 to 8 and presided over by
UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Topfer, the Undersecretary-General of the U.N. and
Executive Director of UNEP, is now on a visit in Abu Dhabi at the
invitation of the General Exhibition Corporation (GEC), the
organizer of the event.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy met with officials of the GEC and the Federal
Environment Agency (FEA) on Wednesday evening and discussed ways
of supporting the environmental exhibition and conference.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference on Thursday, Topfer said
that the environment exhibition and conference showed the UAE's
"dedication to the environment in this part of the world."
</P>
<P>
Brigadier Al Suwaidi, the GEC's Director General, said the
exhibition and conference will be attended by environment
ministers, advisors, decision-makers, prominent scientists and
technical experts.
</P>
<P>
The conference, he said, would discuss sustainable development,
special issues concerning the Middle East and developing
countries, economics, the prevention and control of marine
environmental pollution and other important subjects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
