<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese FM Ends Visit to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister
Masahiko Komura Friday concluded his brief official visit to
Lebanon, the first since the two countries established diplomatic
relations in 1941.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the country, Komura held talks with
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Salim Hoss on regional affairs and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Hoss told reporters that their talks
focused on the Israeli daily aggression on Lebanon, especially
the recent escalated air attacks on Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, eight Lebanese civilians, including a
mother and her six children, had been killed and another seven
civilians wounded in Israeli air raids on eastern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said the Japanese foreign minister expressed his country's
support for Lebanon's legal demand concerning the Israeli
unconditional withdrawal from the country.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government proposed last April to withdraw its
troops from Lebanon provided that the Lebanese government agree a
negotiated security arrangement in advance.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its close ally Syria flatly rejected the offer,
urging the Israeli troops to leave the country without any
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said their talks also covered matters with regard to the
five Japanese Red Army members who were sentenced by Lebanese
court to three years each in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said the question about the five Japanese convicted of
entering Lebanon with forged passports and visas would be raised
up only after they completed their terms in Lebanese prison.
</P>
<P>
Japan has been seeking to extradite these five citizens to the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese foreign minister arrived here from Egypt on Friday
and left for Syria later in the day. He will also visit Jordan,
Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
