<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Energy and Water Development
Benjamin Mwila has appealed to the Zambia Electricity Supply Corporation
(ZESCO) workers to return to work, saying their grievances cannot be
addressed in a crisis situation.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who addressed the striking workers at the ZESCO head
office in Lusaka Friday, said the strike was without the blessing of
government and not in the interest of the country, Zambia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Mwila said it is only prudent that the workers, who he said are
essential to the nation, resume work to allow for their representatives,
management and a government team address their grievances.
</P>
<P>
He said it is important to be disciplined in resolving industrial
disputes, saying there is no justification for the workers to strike.
</P>
<P>
 Striking will only destroy what we have already built, the minister
added.
</P>
<P>
 The ZESCO workers strike commenced in Ndola two days ago and has
spread to the capital Lusaka and other copperbelt towns such as Kitwe.
</P>
<P>
 ln Lusaka, the striking workers charged that management had neglected
them by not fulfilling its promises. Last month, Deputy Minister of the
ministry, Celestino Chibamba reassured the workers that they would be paid
their bonus even after Christmas.  
</P>
