<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Up on Weak U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar spiked
higher Friday, spurred by a weaker U.S. dollar, soaring gold
prices and fading early interest in the euro.
</P>
<P>
The domestic currency added more than three quarters of a U.S.
cent Thursday night, jumping to a five-week high of 63.69 U.S.
cents in early trading here.
</P>
<P>
It dipped to a low of 63.18 U.S. cents during the day, and
ended the session at 63.22 cents from its close Thursday of 62.90.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was also buying 0.5406 euro from 0.5410
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
MMS Standard &AMP; Poor's currency strategist Alex Douglas said the
strong performance in gold Thursday night was one of several
factors impacting positively on the domestic currency.
</P>
<P>
"Also we've had U.S. dollar/yen falling," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It dipped below 110 (yen) at one point, which was a fairly
significant sort of level.
</P>
<P>
"A generally weaker U.S. dollar and a firmer yen help us to
rise."
</P>
<P>
BNP senior strategist Clifford Bennett said Australia had a
history of tracking the yen, the major currency in the region.
</P>
<P>
"The movement in the yen is perhaps some early warning signs
that the Japanese economy might be bottoming and that would
certainly be good for Australia," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the local close the Australian dollar finished trading at
70.16 Japanese yen from 70.72. 
</P>
</TEXT>
