<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cold Air Reduces Urban Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China's urban air quality has
improved significantly over the past few days thanks to strong
cold front gripping most of the nation, according to a report
released by the China Environmental Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
The cold air has helped dissipate accumulated pollutants,
according to experts.
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out that air pollution indexes for
a number of northern cities have continued to rise over the past
seven days.
</P>
<P>
From January 1 to 7, Shantou, Haikou and Xiamen enjoyed
excellent air quality for the first seven days in January, with
Guilin, Zhuhai, Shenzhen and 12 other cities reporting good air
quality.
</P>
<P>
Eleven cities, including Guangzhou and Nanjing reported slight
air pollution during the period, with Tianjin, Shanghai and 10
other cities reporting medium air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Beijing, Lanzhou, Yinchuan, Xining and Hohhot reported serious
air pollution resulting from the large volume of suspended
particles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
