<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Give Top Priority to Agricultural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
give top priority to agricultural development in order to achieve
food security and emancipate rural folk from poverty, President
Joseph Estrada said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a report on his administration's accomplishments in its
first six months, Estrada said that food security and agricultural
development are the two most potent weapons in his administration
all-out battle against poverty as the vast majority of Filipinos
still depend on agriculture for their income and livelihood.
</P>
<P>
In the remaining years of his administration, Estrada said that
he hopes to be able to distribute to farmers 8.2 million of
hectares of land under the Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Program.
</P>
<P>
The government has already attained half its target, or the
distribution of some 4 million hectares of land to farmers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"By the year 2001, the country would be self-sufficient in
rice, corn and sugar with the agriculture modernization program as
the main tool for achieving that goal," he said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that the government will continue to pursue its
10-point agenda for agriculture, which include the expansion of
existing productivity programs, irrigation, post harvest
facilities, research and marketing information, credit assistance,
food price stabilization and the quick response to calamities.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Philippines' economic situation, Estrada said:
"Although our economic growth (in 1998) was not as strong as in
the years before, it kept us out of a recession."
</P>
<P>
The economy proved so resilient that today, the country
continues to enjoy positive growth despite the crisis in Asia, he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Estrada said, 1999 will be a critical year for the
economy, which faces a gross national product growth target of at
least 3 percent so it can go full steam ahead by 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The challenges that we expect to face in 1999 are tests which
we can only pass if we are united as a people... the characters of
our people, the ability to fight back despite the odds, is the
source of resiliency of our economic, political and social
systems," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
