<HEADLINE> 38 Nigerian Soldiers Killed in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Some 38 soldiers of the Nigerian
contingent of the West African peace-keeping force ECOMOG have been killed
in the battle for the control of Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, the
Nigerian newspaper Post Express Friday quoted military sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
 The military sources said that the dead soldiers were flown into
Nigeria
Sunday night alongside wounded soldiers on board the military transport
plane,
the C-130 E Hercules.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were buried at a military cemetary at the Ojo military
barracks in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
However, the Acting Director of Defence Information, Sam Tella denied
knowledge of any corpses being brought into the country from war-torn
Sierra Leone, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
 Sam Tella, as the defence spokesman told reporters Thursday that
though the situation in Sierra Leone was "confusing", military level
consultations were going on
over how to appropriately deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG will not stand by and allow the legitimate government of
President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah to be ousted again, he stressed, adding that "
Nigeria expects normalcy to return to Sierra Leone in the shortest possible
time".
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is the largest provider of troops to the ECOMOG force which was
initially
set up by the Economic Community of the West African States (ECOWAS) in
1990 and currently deployed in Sierra Leone where it ousted a military
junta in February 1998 and reinstated President Kabbah in March last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
