<HEADLINE> Israeli Police tighten Security During Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police decided on
Friday to step up security protections for all candidates for the
prime minister during the current election campaign.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made following Thursday's incident in Tel
Aviv, in which the life of Amnon Lipkin-Shahak was threatened by a
local resident.
</P>
<P>
Shahak, the newly retired chief of general staff of the
defense force and one of the prime minister's candidates, did not
see many smiling faces Thursday in his first campaign foray into
the traditional Likud territory of the outdoor Hatikva market in
south Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
What he did encounter there were a lot of faces in hatred,
fists brandished at him, curses and flying bits of chicken,
tomatos, oranges and even parts of booths aimed at him.
</P>
<P>
What scared him and his campaign staff more was a little guy
shouting at them.
</P>
<P>
The decision to send Shahak into hostile territory immediately
after his announcement of prime minister candidacy was made a
week ago, his staff said, but no one in his election headquarters
foresaw the violent reception he would receive, which was
triggered possibly by his statement on Wednesday that "Netanyahu
is a danger to Israel."
</P>
<P>
The Tel Aviv police have decided to investigate the Thursday
case and the police would not allow anybody to threaten prime
minister candidates during the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Labor party central committee approved Thursday
night the party political bureau's recommendation to hold
primaries for the party's Knesset (parliament) candidates on
February 15.
</P>
<P>
Labor party leader Ehud Barak till now is the sole candidate
for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The Likud party decided to choose party chairman on January
25. Its party chairman will be the candidate for prime
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
