<HEADLINE> Major Cabinet Reshuffle in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Friday announced a major cabinet reshuffle in
which Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi was appointed as
deputy prime minister and home minister.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister's post has been left vacant since
Anwar Ibrahim was sacked as the deputy prime minister and finance
minister, but the finance minister's post was filled up when
Mahathir himself became the first finance minister and appointed
Mustapha Mohamed as second finance minister.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was also the home minister before Friday's reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
In the reshuffle, Special Functions Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin
was appointed as finance minister.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Syed Hahid Albar took over as the new foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
Abang Abu Bakar Mustapha who is minister in the Prime
Minister's Department, was appointed as defense minister.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali was promoted to
minister in the Prime Minister's Department.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir announced the reshuffle at a news conference after
chairing the monthly UMNO (United Malays National Organization)
Supreme Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
The major reshuffle came just one day after Inspector-General
of Police Rahim Noor announced his resignation, assuming the
responsibility for the injuries to former deputy prime minister
Anwar Ibrahim during his police detention.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is on trial in the High Court on four corruption
charges, Thursday filed a memorandum of appeal through his counsel
Karpal Singh at the Court of Appeal registry here, against the
High Court's decision striking out his suit against Mahathir and
the Malaysian government.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was sacked as the deputy prime minister and finance
minister on September 2 last year, claimed his dismissal was
unconstitutional and that Mahathir had contravened Article 43 (5)
of the Federal Constitution in removing him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
