<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Hezbollah Fires Mortar on Northern Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas
fired several mortar shells on western Galilee in northern Israel
Friday morning, but no damage was reported, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Lebanese sources as saying that Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, shelled the areas in response to the
demolition of civilian houses in south Lebanon by Israeli
soldiers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli forces razed 15 civilian houses in Arnoun village
Thursday where Lebanese guerrillas wounded an Israeli soldier a
day earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army believes that Arnoun, largely depopulated by
the conflicts, has been used by guerrillas to place bombs.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah issued a statement after the demolition, warning that
"the arm of the resistance will twist the necks of the criminal
aggressors."
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah has been spearheading a guerrilla war against Israeli
troops since 1985 when Israel set up a self-declared security zone
in south Lebanon with a claimed aim of protecting its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla group also attacked Israeli military outposts in
the western sector of the zone Friday but caused no casualties,
Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have been running high in the 15-kilometer-deep buffer
zone over the last few weeks when Israeli forces killed or wounded
a dozen Lebanese civilians during air strikes against Hezbollah
bases.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah have sporadicly fired Katyusha rockets or mortar
shells into northern Israel in retaliation for Israel's attacks
against Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet last week adopted a proposal submitted by the
army that Israel should strike against Lebanese infrastructure
targets if Israel's northern areas were attacked by Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
But the army chief, Shaul Mofaz, said later that it's not in
the interest of Israel to see an escalation of tensions in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Hezbollah officials as saying Friday that
the sole reason for the existence of Hezbollah in south Lebanon
is the Israeli occupation, and Hezbollah has no intention to
escalate the tensions there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
