<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's New Deputy PM Promises Dedication to Duties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's newly-appointed
Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi promised Friday night
to discharge his duties as best he can and with full dedication.
</P>
<P>
The 59-year old Abdullah was named the deputy prime minister
and home minister earlier Friday in a cabinet reshuffle announced
by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad after a Supreme Council meeting
of the ruling United Malays National Organization (UMNO).
</P>
<P>
Thanking Mahathir for his trust, Abdullah, who is one of the
three UMNO vice-presidents, told reporters "I was surprised
because my other colleagues considered for the post by the prime
minister are just as capable."
</P>
<P>
He said he needed Mahathir's guidance in discharging his new
duties and responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah also said that he hoped to get cooperation from his
colleagues in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar took over from Abdullah as
foreign minister in the reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who joined UMNO in 1965, became active in politics in
1978 when he was elected the Member of Parliament and retained his
parliamentary constituency for five terms until today.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah was deputy federal territory minister in 1980, his
first post in the government. In 1981 when he was elected to the
UMNO Supreme Council, Abdullah was made minister in the Prime
Minister's Department in Mahathir's first cabinet. Abdullah also
served as minister of education in 1984, minister of Defense in
1986.
</P>
<P>
He was made foreign minister in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who failed to retain the UMNO vice-presidency in 1993
but was appointed a member of the UMNO Supreme Council, made a
comeback when he was elected vice-president for the 1996/1999
term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
