<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Sharply Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The froth that had engulfed the
Australian sharemarket evaporated Friday as shares closed sharply
lower, with blue chips leading the market down as concern surfaced
about the future impact of the strong Australian dollar on
export-oriented stocks.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said another contributor to the fall was the sharp rise
in the Japanese yen against a weakening U.S. currency and falls
sustained in the Japanese equities market.
</P>
<P>
They also said the smaller premium on the futures market's
share price index contract over the benchmark all ordinaries index
indicated "a little bit of non-confidence" and "cooling-off" in
the physical market.
</P>
<P>
"Now we might see a little bit of sobriety coming into the
market," said senior dealer Stuart Smith of Henderson Charlton
Jones.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries, after breaking through the 2,900-point
barrier for the first time Thursday and dipping to close at a
record high, Friday dropped 41 points, or 1.42 percent, to
2,856.3, off a high of 2,897.3 and a low of 2,850.8.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp. led the blue chip falls, with its
scrip losing 43 cents, or 3.93 percent, and its preferred scrip
losing 45, or 4.43 percent.
</P>
<P>
Bank stocks also sustained losses after the share prices of the
National Australia Bank, Commonwealth Bank of Australia and
Westpac Banking Corp. reached new heights Thursday, with the
banking index falling 1.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
NAB dipped 21.9 cents, Westpac plunged 40.3, CBA dropped 50 and
ANZ Banking Group lost 26 cents.
</P>
<P>
Among other leading industrial stocks, Telstra Corp. closed
seven cents lower, Brambles Industries lost 94.3 cents, Lend Lease
fell 34.4, Woolworths slumped 10.
</P>
<P>
But Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus, which topped turnover in shares
traded, bucked the negative trend, gaining three cents on a volume
of 16.8 million shares.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, BHP plunged 36.2, or 3.03 percent, Rio
Tinto dropped 33.8, but WMC gained four.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials finished 76 points lower at 5,173.3 and the
all resources index closed 11.7 points lower at 950.5.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a thin 344.76 million shares valued at
1.02 billion Australian dollars (647.7 million U.S. dollars), with
678 falls outnumbering 536 rises and 404 stocks remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by strong gains in gold bullion prices in New York
Thursday night, the gold index also defied the negative sentiment,
closing 20.5 points higher at 1,135.7. Gold bullion closed 2.90
higher at 291.15 U.S. dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
