<HEADLINE> Estrada: PAL to Be Managed by Cathay Executives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada announced here Friday that the Philippine Airlines (PAL)
will be managed by the executives of the Hong Kong-based Cathay
Pacific Airways under an agreement reached by the two airlines.
</P>
<P>
In a report on his administration's accomplishments in its
first six months Friday night, Estrada said, "The Philippine
Airlines has just forged an agreement with Cathay Pacific and
effective immediately, PAL will be managed by Cathay Pacific
executives."
</P>
<P>
But he did not elaborate on any future strategic cooperation
between the two airlines.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued Friday night, PAL said the Board of
Directors of Philippine Airlines and the Interim Rehabilitation
Receiver of PAL approved Friday a five-year technical services
agreement with Regent Star Services Ltd. (RSS), a Hong Kong-based
aviation management consultancy firm.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, five former top executives of Cathay
Pacific Airways, all RSS partners, will serve as advisers to PAL
management in their respective areas of expertise.
</P>
<P>
"This group would have formed the same management team had the
PAL-Cathay partnership pushed through last year," PAL said.
</P>
<P>
It said the approval of the agreement is in line with PAL's
commitment to all its stakeholders to improving management
performance.
</P>
<P>
It is also intended to deliver a continuous stream of tangible
improvements in PAL operations, particularly during the
implementation of the flag carrier's rehabilitation plan, PAL
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
