<HEADLINE> Philippine President Optimistic of Peace, Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Friday that with the continued support of the
people, his country can better secure peace and prosperity in
1999.
</P>
<P>
In a report on his administration's accomplishments in its
first six months, Estrada said that despite the Asian financial
crisis, his government has maintained economic stability to
prevent recession, and upheld peace and order and the rule of law
in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Our experience over the past six months has once again
displayed that it is precisely during these difficult times that
we can bring out the best in the Filipino."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the first six months are only the start of a
bigger battle against national problems like poverty.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Filipinos to continue efforts to realize their
potentials despite external pressures and limited resources.
</P>
<P>
For 1999, Estrada said, he intends to continue a
market-oriented approach to stimulate the economy and attract
investors and at the same time to maintain peace and order.
</P>
<P>
"The challenges that we expect to face in 1999 are tests which
we can only pass if we are united as a people... The character of
our people, the ability to fight back despite the odds, are the
source of resiliency of our economic, political and social
systems," he said. 
</P>
