<HEADLINE> HK Stocks Climb 9 percent in First Week of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong share prices surged
over 9 percent in the first trading week of 1999, with the local
stocks extending their gains on Friday amid expectations of a
local interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth consecutive session of gains. The key Hang
Seng Index (HSI) rose 29.13 points, or 0.27 percent, to close at
10,722.7 Friday.
</P>
<P>
Over the whole week, the shares have climbed 913.53 points, or
9.31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Friday's turnover amounted to 7.877 billion HK dollars (1.01 bi
llion U.S. dollars), 2.715 billion HK dollars (348 million U.S.
dollars) less than that of Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said some overseas fund buying was evident with hopes
that the weaker U.S. dollar will help Hong Kong pull out of the
recession faster than forecasters are currently predicting.
</P>
<P>
The market opened strongly with the HSI rising 19.58 points,
or 0.18 percent, to 10,713.15. The stocks then went up 148.69
points, or 1.39 percent, to close Friday's morning session at
10,842.26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
