<HEADLINE> Share Prices Extend Rise on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to rise
on Singapore Stock Market Friday, ending the week with a bang
after making hefty gains for the last three days.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said foreign funds managers went on plowing back their
money into the market, despite the dismal performance on Wall
Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
Wall Street's poor showing failed to dampen investors' spirit
and their funds continued to be poured into the market, dealers
noted.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment was encouraging for many market players, they added.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) climbed up 27.3 points
to close at 1,545.18 in active trading, off their intra-day high
of 1,554.48 points.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover decreased to 395.59 million units worth
891.1 million Singapore dollars (532.83 million U.S. dollars).
Rises edged out falls by 258 to 40 with 122 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
PSC was the most favorite stock of the day with a volume of
22.09 million units traded. DBS Land was the second most-heavily
traded share with a turnover of 14.91 million units. KepTL was
next with 13.44 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 remained at the top of the actives' chart of the
day with a jump of 160 cents to 28 Singapore dollars. It was
followed by GE Life that surged 155 cents to 10.9 Singapore
dollars. Bukit Sem climbed 95 cents to finish at 10.1 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SIA F was the biggest loser of the day,
plummeting 60 cents to 12.9 Singapore dollars. C &AMP; C was next,
retreating 50 cents to 6.25 Singapore dollars. DBS F sank 40 cents
to end at 15.20 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
