<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Delegation to Observe China's Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- An 11-member delegation from
the U.S.-based Carter Center is in Chongqing, the well-known
mountainous city in southwest China, to observe local elections
for people's deputies on the township level.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will be the first foreign nongovernmental
organization to observe elections for local legislators in China.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the center have previously observed
elections for members of grassroots village committees.
</P>
<P>
"I'm here to observe direct elections in Chongqing's township
and personally observe the progress China has made in
strengthening democracy on the township level," said Charles
Costello, director of the center's Democracy Program.
</P>
<P>
The delegation attended a meeting in which senior lawmakers
from the Chongqing Municipal People's Congress outlined
procedures for election of people's deputies at the township
level. Members of the delegation plan to observe elections in
Rongchang and Dazu counties.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, which covers 80,000 sq.km. and has a population of
30 million people, joined Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin as
China's fourth municipality. The municipality is the largest
industrial and commercial metropolis in southwest China and the
major economic center in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, some 20 million people in 1,478
townships under the jurisdiction of the municipality are
qualified to vote.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
