<HEADLINE> Diplomatic Efforts Needed to End Angolan Conflicts: Chissano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 8 (XInhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano has
said that the international community should make more diplomatic efforts
to end conflicts in Angola and bring UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi to the
negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
Chissano made the remarks Thursday at a press conference in Chimoio,
central west Angola, after meeting with visiting Malawian President Bakili
Muluzi, the Noticias newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is to settle the conflict through negotiations instead of
 through military force. It is our hope that Savimbi will return to the
negotiation table," he said.
</P>
<P>
 On the issue of Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Chissano said, his
government was worried about the political crisis in the DRC and hopes that
the people of the DRC will enjoy lasting peace, social and political
stability.  Chissano also pledged his support for all diplomatic efforts
by other countries to settle the crisis.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Muluzi said the wars in Angola and the DRC have
hampered the development of the two countries and the African continent,
painting a poor image of Africa in the eyes of international society.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the war in Angola will end if Savimbi of the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) gives up its belligerent
mentality.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also revealed that he and Muluzi also discussed issues
concerning bilateral cooperation. He announced that ministers of the two
countries will soon hold talks in Maputo on the use of Nacala Corridor in
the north of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
