<HEADLINE> Nigeria Consults Allies Over S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has consulted
regional allies over the situation in Sierra Leone, according to a This Day
report Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar met Executive
Secretrary of the Economic Community of the West African States (ECOWAS)
Lansana Kouyate Thursday to discuss the situation in Freetown, capital of
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Mallam Mohammed Haruna, Chief Press Secretary to General Abubakar
disclosed Thursday that Nigeria also held talks with Guinean President
General Lansana Conte and other regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian officials held discussions with Sierra Lone's envoy
to Nigeria Joseph Blell and representatives of several other diplomatic
missions in Nigeria Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The combined force of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) troops
and ex-junta soldiers launched military attacks on capital Freetown
Wednesday and claimed that they controlled the east end of the city.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said that the fighting continued Thursday between the Nigeria-
led West African peace-keeping force stationed in the country to back the
Sierra Lone government, and the rebels as both sides fought over the
central commercial district.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Defense Ministry spokesman Lt. Col. Sam Tella said Thursday
that Nigeria expected the situation to be restored to normal soon.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah said at a press conference
held at Freetown's Lungi airport that he had reached a seven-day cease-fire
agreement with rebel leader Foday Sankoh, who was sentenced to death for
supporting the coup that ousted t. Kabbah in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to Kabbah, the truce period will be used for mediation by
Cote d'Ivoire and Togo, which currently chairs the Economic Community of
the West African States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
