<HEADLINE> Britain Commits Fund for AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
announced Friday that his country would spend 100 million pounds(165
million U.S. Dollars) in the next three years to help fight HIV/AIDS
globally.
</P>
<P>
"We aim to commit up to 100 million British pounds over the next three
years on effective action to tackle AIDS globally and are intensifying our
support for effective action against AIDS in Africa," the British embassy
quoted Blair as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Blair was visiting an AIDS hospice in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"HIV/AIDS is a massive threat to the development achievements of the
last 50 years. New figures for HIV infection in Africa are appalling."
</P>
<P>
"Prevention is the urgent priority. A vaccine is the ultimate aim," he
said.
</P>
<P>
HIV or Human immuno-deficiency virus leads to full blown AIDS (acquired
immuno-deficiency syndrome).
</P>
<P>
Sub-Sahara Africa is currently the worst hit region in the world. More
than two-thirds of all HIV infections occur in the region. Africa also see
83 percent of all deaths attributable to AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
