<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Builds North-Capital Railway Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The project is progressing fast
for building a direct rail-link between Bangladesh's northeastern
part and the capital Dhaka and the eastern part through the
Bangabandhu (Jammuna) Bridge, The Bangladesh Observer daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The project, involving over 11.55 billion taka (about 238.1
million U.S. dollars), is scheduled to be completed in two phases
by the end of May 2001 and the work of the first phase began on
September 4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In the first phase, a 94-kilometer-long mixed-gauge railway
line will be constructed from Joydevpur to Jamtail in the northern
district of Sirajganj at a cost of about 5.15 billion taka (about
106.2 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Samwhan and France's TSO Gedi companies are
jointly carrying out the project, which includes construction of
bridges and culverts, nine railway stations, laying of pebbles and
track fittings.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase, some 250 kilometers of broad-gauge railway
line from Jamtail to Ishwardi via Parbatipur will be turned into
mixed gauge after the completion of the first phase.
</P>
<P>
At present, Bangladesh has more than 4,000 kilometers of
railway lines throughout the country with a total area of 143,393
square kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
