<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quoting Airline Fares in Foreign Currency Illegal in Zimbabwe: M inister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 8 (Xinhua) -- It is illegal for any airline operating
from Zimbabwe to quote air fares in U.S. Dollars or any other foreign
currency, Minister of Industry and Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira has said.
</P>
<P>
The Board of Airline Representatives confirmed Wednesday its decision
to quote air fares on domestic, regional and international routes in U.S.
Dollars, saying the move was meant to stabilize operations and avert
frequent increases, the daily Herald reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government's intervention means all airlines operating from
Zimbabwe which had started to quote their fares in U.S. Dollars have to
revert to the old system of charging their clients in local currency.
</P>
<P>
Shamuyarira Thursday told the Herald that Zimbabwean laws categorically
barred all transactions from being done in foreign currency and that all
airlines wishing to continue operating in the country had to abide by the
law and use local currency.
</P>
<P>
"According to the laws of Zimbabwe, the Zimbabwean Dollar is the legal
tender for all transactions of goods and services in the country. If the
airlines want to keep flying, they should continue to quote their fares in
Zimbabwean Dollars," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that by quoting fares in U.S. Dollars, fares were going
to almost double and go beyond the reach of ordinary Zimbabweans, although
special discounted fares were still going to be offered until March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pierce, Schnyder to Meet in Hardcourt Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Mary Pierce of France
will meet second seed Patty Schnyder in Saturday's final of the
165,000 U.S.dollar Australian Women's Hardcourt Championships at
Gold Coast, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The world No.7 beat Romanian Irina Spirlea 4-6, 6-4, 6-1 and
will meet second seed Patty Schnyder in the final.
</P>
<P>
Schnyder of Switzerland defeated defending champion Ai
Sugiyama of Japan 6-2, 7-6 (7-5) for the chance to win her sixth
Women's Tennis Association title.
</P>
<P>
Pierce looked in trouble early against world No.15 Spirlea who
was let down with crucial double faults and 43 unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
In the first set Spirlea broke Pierce in her initial service
game but the Frenchwoman broke back in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian then broke her opponent's usual pin-point serve
in the fifth game to win the set.
</P>
<P>
The second set went to serve until the ninth game when Pierce
broke and in the final set she stepped up a gear to win the match.
</P>
<P>
After the match Pierce said Spirlea was too good for her in
the first set.
</P>
<P>
Schnyder's defeat of Sugiyama was the worst result for the
diminutive Japanese who came second at the Hope Island Tennis
Club in 1997 and won in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Sugiyama played her usual consistent baseline game in the
first set but was no match for Schnyder's left hand curling
serves.
</P>
<P>
In the second, Sugiyama broke in the 11th game but Schnyder
broke back in the 12th to leave a tie-break to decide the set.
</P>
<P>
Sugiyama was up 4-2 in the tie-break but a dubious line call
gave her a double fault and allowed Schnyder back in to win the
match.
</P>
<P>
In the doubles final, American Corina Morariu and Larissa
Neiland of Latvia will meet Australian Kristine Kunce and
Spirlea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
