<HEADLINE> Manila, Rebel Group to Resume Talks in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have agreed to resume their
formal peace talks in the first week of February, a senior
official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, National Security Adviser Alexander
Aguirre said the agreement was reached during an informal meeting
between the chairmen of the government and MILF panels Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It was a very positive informal meeting in order to set the
schedule of the peace negotiations sometime in the first week of
February, and we believe that this is a positive sign that the
peace talks will be continued well on both sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 1,200-strong MILF, the major rebel group based in Mindanao,
is fighting for an independent Muslim state in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Although the government and the MILF started peace talks a year
ago, the two sides failed to reach any agreement on important
issues, such as the MILF's demand for an independent state.
</P>
