<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Bans Forced Virginity Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Minister of Justice
Hasan Denizkurdu has issued a decree to stop the practice of
forced gynecological exams to determine if women and girls are
virgins.
</P>
<P>
Local Daily News Friday quoted Denizkurdu as saying that girls
in state orphanages, prisoners and sometimes even foreign
tourists staying in hotel rooms with male companions have been
subjected to gynecological tests against their will.
</P>
<P>
He said that the exams "hurt the dignity, modesty and
feelings" of women, adding that the exams can only be required by
a judge if such tests are required as evidence in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
While human rights groups have long denounced the practice,
many conservative Turkish families defend the tests as a way of
deterring girls from straying and damaging marriage prospects.
</P>
<P>
In some more traditional regions of Turkey, it is hard for
women to travel alone with male friends.
</P>
<P>
In Turkey, women wear red ribbons on their wedding gowns to
signal their virginity.
</P>
<P>
Hotel management can demand proof of marriage from couples
before giving them rooms. In most cases, hotel management would
complain to police who would then take the women away to have the
medical exams performed by medical staff.
</P>
<P>
In one reported case, a German journalist was forced to
undergo a medical test to determine whether she had had sexual
intercourse while staying at a hotel with a male friend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0152 </DOCNO>
