<HEADLINE> Jones to Defend Titles against Challenger Frazier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- WBC and WBA
light-heavyweight champion Roy Jones will defend his crowns in a
bout against challenger Richard Frazier in his hometown
Pensacola, Florida on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Jones is 38-1 with 32 knockouts. Frazier is 18-3 with one
drawn and seven knockouts.
</P>
<P>
Jones will be 30 one week after the fight. "Any time a
southpaw is involved, it's never a mismatch," said Jones, who
will meet his third consecutive lefty.
</P>
<P>
"He's the kind of guy who I wouldn't mind my kids looking up
to. If you're gonna get beat you might as well get beat by a good
dude. But I'm not planning to get beat," he said in Pensacola.
</P>
<P>
The 39-year-old Frazier has been a New York police officer for
17 years and was elevated to top contender shortly after signing
with promoter Don King.
</P>
<P>
His 300,000-dollar prize money hit record high in his career,
compared to his prior best of 12,000 dollars fighting in clubs.
</P>
<P>
"I know the writers don't have much hope for me, but I have
hope for myself," Frazier said.
</P>
<P>
Another defending game on the same day will take place between
unbeaten International Boxing Federation (IBF) lightweight champ
ion Shane Mosley, 27, who is 30-0 with 28 knockouts and
24-year-old Golden Johnson who is 15-2 with two drawn and 10
knockouts.
</P>
<P>
Mosley has won six consecutive title defenses by knockout
since capturing the crown in August of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
