<HEADLINE> Ugandan MPs to Summon Vice President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Uganda's parliamentary standing
committee on national economy has resolved to summon Vice President
Specioza Kazibwe and two ministers over the stalled Budget Bill.
</P>
<P>
The committee, chaired by Isaac Isanga Musumba, made the decision
Thursday, the New Vision daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said the vice president, Finance Minister Gerald Ssendaula and
Parliamentary Affairs Minister Martin Aliker should appear before the
committee next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kagole Kivumbi, spokesman to Parliament, told Xinhua in a telephone
interview Friday morning that it is a normal thing for ministers to appear
before committees.
</P>
<P>
"It's normal. It's not a disgrace for the person to be summoned. The
ministers have the duty to explain to parliamentary committees. The only
person who cannot be summoned is the President," Kivumbi said.
</P>
<P>
The MPs are opposed to the current practice whereby the government
presents a final budget and merely asks for parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe and the ministers are to explain why the Budget Bill has not
yet been tabled to the House.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe is reportedly to appear in her capacity as the leader of
government business in parliament. Thursday's summon by the MPs is the
second for Kazibwe in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
She is scheduled to appear before the select committee on agriculture
Tuesday over her role in the valley dams saga in which millions of U.S.
Dollars earmarked for building valley dams was missing.
</P>
<P>
Kazibwe, who is also the Minister of Agriculture, is allegedly
responsible for the mismanagement of the the valley dam fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
