<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to start AIDS Education in School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will soon start an
education campaign against AIDS in schools across the country, Xinhua
learned here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Ministry of Health said students, teachers and parents will,
beginning next month, be shown films and given lectures on the disease.
</P>
<P>
The program, funded by the World Bank, will also involve financing drama,
poetry and song competition on HIV/AIDS at the grass-root level.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.5 million Kenyans have contracted the AIDS virus since 1980,
and over half a million of these victims have died, according to sources
from the Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A number of AIDS cases have been reported in Kenyan secondary schools
and colleges, long thought to be free of the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
According to Director Julius Meme of Medical Services under the ministry,
the campaign will be centered at the district level and be coordinated by
district medical officials in collaboration with inter-sectoral AIDS
committee. The ministry has already allocated 35 million Shillings (some
0.6 million U.S. Dollars) to all districts in readiness for the campaign,
Meme noted. "It is anticipated that the school programs will augment
community AIDS education program," Meme said, adding that the ministry
wanted to ensure that 70 percent of students in final year are able to
cite at least two ways of preventing HIV/AIDS.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter Knocked out of Championships in Adelaide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Dual U.S. Open champion
Patrick Rafter was knocked out of the Adelaide Men's Hardcourt
Championships in the second round in Adelaide, Australia, on
Friday in a shock upset by Czech veteran Slava Dosedel.
</P>
<P>
Dosedel, ranked 64th in the world, eliminated the world No.4
7-5, 6-4 in a match postponed from last night because of rain.
</P>
<P>
Rafter said he felt sluggish on court and was lacking
motivation after two hard years on the ATP tour and needed some
good wins to gain confidence going into the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
"I was a little sluggish out there, when I'm not moving well I
don't play well," he told the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"He (Dosedel) played well and he deserved the luck. He has
obviously been doing a lot more work than I have."
</P>
<P>
But Rafter said the nagging left knee injury which forced him
to take a two month break at the end of last year had fully
healed.
</P>
<P>
Dosedel said he was pleased with his solid game because he
didn't allow Rafter a chance to break back in either set.
</P>
<P>
"It was a good start to the year for me to beat a top 10
player," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Adelaide teenager Lleyton Hewitt has taken the next
step towards defending his title by advancing to the
quarter-finals with a three sets victory over Jiri Novak, also of
the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Hewitt, who was 3-2 up in the final set when
rain interrupted play last night, took the game 7-6 (7-2), 2-6,
6-4 when play resumed Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hewitt, ranked 100th, said there was a lot more pressure on
him this year compared with last year when he stunned the tennis
world by winning the tournament, then named the Australian Men's
Hardcourt.
</P>
<P>
"I could go out there and no one knew me last year and this
year, you're sort of a marked man," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hewitt became the fourth Australian to advance to a
quarter-finals, and will play Dosedel Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Scott Draper and Michael Tebbutt are battling for a berth in
the final four, while Jason Stoltenberg will meet Zimbabwean
Byron Black and Swede Thomas Enqvist will play Slovakian Dominik
Hrbaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
