<HEADLINE> Lack of Funds Hampers AIDS Education in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Lack of funds, textbooks and
teachers has prevented Tanzania from effectively carrying out AIDS
education among students, an official with the Ministry of Education and
Culture has said.
</P>
<P>
M. Sawaya, a coordinator of School AIDS Education Program of the
ministry, was quoted by Friday's Daily Mail as saying that the curriculum
on AIDS was started in 1990 but was not materialized until last year due to
financial constraints.
</P>
<P>
Other obstacles to AIDS education are absence of teachers who have
special knowledge on AIDS and textbooks on the deadly disease, the official
revealed to the paper Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, education programs on AIDS, HIV and Sexually Transmitted
Diseases (STDs) are implemented in primary schools, secondary schools as
well as teaching training colleges.
</P>
<P>
The National AIDS Control Program (NACP) said it hoped HIV/AIDS
transmission could be curbed by giving education to as many people as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics indicated that in Tanzania, which has a population
of 32 million, around 520,000 people have been infected with AIDS while a
total of 1.5 million are carriers of HIV virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The government said AIDS cases are still increasing at an alarming rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
