<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Market lots for Homes in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Housing Ministry is to
market lots in the Palestinian territories for building 3,729
residential units, according to a ministry document carried by
the local paper Ha'aretz Friday.
</P>
<P>
The document said that another 1,320 lots are to be made
available at the politically controversial site of Har Homa in
southern Jerusalem, on top of the 1,000 recently put on the
market there after a year's freeze.
</P>
<P>
The tenders to be issued for lots in West Bank
settlements include 500 units in Ariel, 500 in Alfei Menash
and 400 in the ultra-orthodox Emanuel.
</P>
<P>
In the areas near Jerusalem, the program includes the
construction of 811 homes in Givat Ze'ev, 636 in the
ultra-orthodox Betar, 600 in Ma'akeh Adumim, 182 in Adam and
100 at Efrat. Another 404 apartment units are slated for
settlement of Tsur Bahe, near Bethlehem, but political objections
may delay this project.
</P>
<P>
Of the lots on the market in 1999, the document added,
19.3 percent are earmarked for the orthodox and ultra-orthodox
communities, down from 21.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Based on this partial program, which does not include
projects of the Israel Lands Administration (ILA), and on
statements made by ILA, the Housing Ministry and the ILA will
not meet the government's quota of 60,000 residential units for
1999.
</P>
<P>
The Housing Ministry generally markets downscale housing, much
of it in areas remote from the center of Israel, while the
ILA deals mostly with more prestigious sites such as Tel Aviv
and other cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
