<HEADLINE> No Deal Yet on DRC Cease-fire: Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba said
there was no consensus for a cease-fire in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) conflict, but he was optimistic that talks planned for next week in
Lusaka would be fruitful.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba was speaking Thursday after a two-hour meeting with Rwandan
President Pasteur Bizimungu and Vice President and Defense Minister Major
General Paul Kagame in the Rwandan capital Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Friday quoted Chiluba as saying "Up to now the dialog
is promising and is continuing. Our intention is to see peace restored in
Congo."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bizimungu described the talks with Chiluba as "very
interesting."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, who now travels to Uganda, is considered neutral in the multi-
national war in Congo and is spearheading efforts under the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) to promote a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda are providing military backing to Congolese rebels
who began a campaign to oust President Laurent Kabila last August.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad are supporting Congolese government
forces.
</P>
<P>
A regional summit on peace in the DRC which had been scheduled for last
month was postponed for three times because Kabila refused to have direct
talks with the rebels. It is now due to take place from January 12 to 15.
and now Kabila proposed to meet the rebels in Kinshasa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
