<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Economic Growth Distressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Contrary to official estimates that show
the Kenyan economy grew at 1.6 percent in 1998, the Economist Intelligence
Unit said productive activities rose only by a distressing one percent, a
statistic which will marginally improve to 1.6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
In its latest country report on Kenya, the technical arm of the Britain-
based Economist magazine noted that after a year in which poor weather and
economic mismanagement conspired to produce a severe downturn in most
sectors, "indications are that 1999 will see a modest recovery to 1.6
percent real growth."
</P>
<P>
The People newspaper Friday quoted the report as saying that the
spending cutbacks and victory over the teachers' strike last year have put
the government in a stronger position to achieve its target of a balanced
budget.
</P>
<P>
Despite the regime's failure to deal with all of the International
Monetary Fund governance demands, the fund appears set to re-establish
lending toward the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
"Into 1999, the continued depressed growth of coffee, sugar, tourism and
manufacturing will hinder any significant recovery until later in the year,
despite lower interest rates. Thus, we are forecasting real GDP growth of
no more than 1.6 percent in 1999, but growth will continue to recover,
albeit slowly, to two percent in 2000," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report estimated that agriculture in Kenya grew negatively to -0.2
percent last year from 1.2 percent in 1997 and is expected to grow to 1.4
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing sector grew by 1.5 percent in 1998, down from 1.9 percent
in 1997 and will grow by three percent this year and 3.5 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Services sector dropped from 2.9 percent in 1997 to 1.3 percent in 1998
and will improve marginally to 1.6 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
