<HEADLINE> Euro  Makes Debut in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LUSAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A number of commercial banks in Zambia
are taking measures to smooth transactions in Euro, the new European
currency launched eight days ago.
</P>
<P>
Some commercial banks including Barclays Bank and Standard Chartered
bank in Lusaka have already started displaying exchange rates of the Kwacha,
 Zambian currency, against the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Some banks have not started transaction in the Euro, saying they want
to gather more details about the new currency before dealing it in their
foreign exchange trade.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank chief dealer Wise Silumbu was quoted by Friday's Zambia
Daily Mail as saying that the bank's policy is to keep in step with the
changing international financial and economic circumstances and has
therefore taken measures to ensure that transactions involving the major
currencies including Euro are facilitated by the bank as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We are not an island and therefore always endeavor to provide all the
necessary services to our clients at all times for their convenience," he
said.
</P>
<P>
At Indo-Zambia Bank, however, the Euro transaction has not been
conducted as management adopted a "wait and see" approach.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange manager of the bank Shukla Satish said the bank will
begin transacting in the currency only after gathering more concrete data
on it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
