<HEADLINE> Chinese Professors Getting Stricter Evaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-four professors at East
China Teachers' University's college of science and engineering
recently had to fill in forms to answer questions about their own
views of their teaching and scientific research ability, work
load, and achievements, according to today's Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
After filling in the forms, they were subject to a ten-minute
examination process organized by academic authorities who will
decide whether or not to hire them, based on the assessment
results, said the Shanghai-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Those who are found to be unqualified will be asked to improve
their work and academic performance, while those who are found to
be capable will be given a 200 yuan (24 U.S. dollars) monthly
stipend.
</P>
<P>
One 50-year-old mathematics professor, Chen Zhijie, said that
this was the first time he had ever been asked to take part in
such an examination, and most said that they felt they were under
more pressure when they heard the college's decision.  
</P>
</TEXT>
