<HEADLINE> Beijing Getting Tough With Illegal Publications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Authorities in the Chinese
capital seized 800,000 illegal publications and 1.2 million
pirated discs in the past year, China Youth Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Public security offices focused on publications which are
politically incorrect and pornographic audio and video products.
In several sting operations, 2,800 people were detained and 190
offenders were put in jail, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Police also arrested people who sold illegal publications on
the street, and customs officers seized 117,000 illegal books and
3,575 video tapes. People who leased houses to the law breakers
were also subject to penalties, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Authorities say they will have a further look at the leases of
private houses, especially in suburban areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
