<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Imposes New Inspection on Electronic Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- China's State Administration
for Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine and the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) have decided on a
mandatory magnetic compatibility inspection for 6 types of imports
 d electronic items as of January 1, to protect the environment
and lives and property.
</P>
<P>
Some imported items are reported to have caused serious
magnetic disturbances in telecommunications, radio broadcasts,
and certain appliances and to have damaged people's health or
caused accidental deaths.
</P>
<P>
The inspection will be mandatory for personal computers,
monitors, printers, switches, television sets, and stereo
equipment. And, starting January 1, 2000, exporters of these 6
kinds of products will need an import commodity safety license
from the administration, and will have to fix a safety
certificate on the products before they can be imported.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration for Entry-Exit Inspection and
Quarantine says it plans to expand the compulsory inspection list
gradually to include more imported products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German FM: Hungary's Accession to EU Far Too Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer said here Thursday that it is still too
early to consider a specific timetable for Hungary's entry to the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference following talks with his
Hungarian counterpart Martony Janos, Fischer said Germany hoped
that Hungary would be able to enter the EU as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said European integration was the only option for the
European countries. In the post-Cold War era, the EU should no
longer rest its eyes on the west. The EU's eastward expansion is
also in the German interests.
</P>
<P>
However, he said it was impractical to discuss Hungary's entry
time now. The EU would finalize the earliest date for the EU
expansion by the end of the year or the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the accession negotiations with the six countries
aspiring for EU membership including Hungary, Fischer said
Germany, which assumed the EU presidency in the first half of
1999, would honor its obligations for the implementation of the
EU expansion process.
</P>
<P>
He said that, by the end of July, 15 of the 31 points involved
in the negotiations would be put on the agenda. He reiterated
that the precondition for the EU expansion was the fulfillment of
the organization's internal reforms.
</P>
<P>
The EU planned to complete its Agenda 2000 for its internal
reforms by the end of March, which the German foreign minister
said, would require the related countries to make concessions for
the elimination of the EU's internal differences. It would be a
hard nut to crack, he added.
</P>
<P>
Martony believed that the EU would be able to reach agreement
on the Agenda 2000. He said the launch of the single European
currency - the euro would accelerate the elimination of the i
nternal differences for all differences would manifest themselves
through the euro.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who arrived here Thursday on a one-day visit to
Budapest, also held separate talks with Hungarian President Goncz
Arpad and Prime Minister Orban Viktor.
</P>
<P>
Hungary, in its bid for entry to EU, has repeatedly pledged
that it would meet the criteria for EU accession by 2000 and
hoped that it would become a full EU member in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Some EU member states including Germany, however, opposed to
any rush in the expansion drive. They insisted that the accession
issue would not be raised for deliberations until the winding up
of the EU internal reforms and the first candidates would not be
admitted prior to 2006. 
</P>
</TEXT>
