<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- An ambitious 150 million
Australian dollar (94.5 million U.S. dollars) tourism campaign
estimated to reach 300 million people over the next three years
was launched by the Australian Tourism Commission Friday.
</P>
<P>
The campaign focuses on five key tourism markets, and it
represents Australia's largest ever overseas tourism push, bigger
than the famous "put a shrimp on the barbie" ads featuring Paul
Hogan in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Federal Tourism Minister Jackie Kelly said in a statement that
she was confident the advertising campaign would take the number
of overseas tourists visiting Australia to more than five million
in 2001, up from 4.1 million last year.
</P>
<P>
She said the advertisements showed the irreverent, humorous
side of Australians, while highlighting traditional tourist
attractions such as beaches and koalas.
</P>
<P>
"The optimistic, colorful and welcoming personality of
Australia is what sets us apart from other countries - it's our
product differentiation," she said.
</P>
<P>
In ad-speak, the promotion is called the Brand Australia
Millennium Campaign.
</P>
<P>
It has separate campaigns for each of Australia's five major
tourism markets - Japan, North America, New Zealand, Europe and
Asia. 
