<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Develop Way To Use Face To Open Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A person can now open a safe
without a key or a fingerprint in just four seconds merely by
appearing in front of a new "intelligent" safe that was developed
at China's Harbin Engineering University.
</P>
<P>
The head of the design group, Yin Zhenliang, says that it is
much safer than conventional safes and the owner no longer need
worry about losing a key or forgetting a digital sequence, and it
is suitable for banks and national defense or public security
offices.
</P>
<P>
A small computer and video camera in the safe identify the
owner and take a photo of any unwelcome visitor.
</P>
<P>
It takes a technician about two hours to install. If the safe
gets a new owner, technicians can open it with the help of the
previous owner and add the image of the new owner. And, if an
intruder tries to open the safe, it can emit a loud alarm that
can be wired to security services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
