<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Capital Keeps Sinking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The earth of the plain around
Beijing has been sinking over the past decade, mainly because of
the excessive use of subterranean water.
</P>
<P>
The village of Zhaocun in suburban Daxing County, the
Dongsanqi area in Changping County and the southern part of
Shunyi County have suffered the most, with a maximum drop of 363
millimeters.
</P>
<P>
The subsidence has caused damage to some underground
facilities, breaking pipes and other structures.
</P>
<P>
It has been attributed to the excessive development of
subterranean water, that reaches some 200 million cubic meters
each year.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has over 10 million people, but its per capita water
resources are only about 300 cubic meters, or only 15 percent of
the country's average and 4 percent of the world's average.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government is looking for ways to restrict the
use of groundwater.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
