<HEADLINE> Investments in Bangladesh's Two EPZs Rise to 320.2 Mln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The investments in Bangladesh's
Dhaka and Chittagong export processing zones (EPZs) rose to about
320.2 million U.S. dollars in the last two fiscal years against
cumulative investments of 197.5 million dollars in the previous 13
years till the 1995-96 fiscal year, The Financial Express daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statistics were revealed at the 16th governors' meeting of
the Bangladesh Export Processing Zone Authority (BEPZA) held here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 fiscal year, the volume of export by the BEPZA
stood at 636 million dollars, up by about 89 percent over the
previous fiscal year's 337 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The total employment in the two EPZs rose by 76 percent to
76,000 from 43,183 two years ago, and besides, after the
completion of 28 more industries in the two EPZs, employment will
be created for an additional 17,200 people and investment would
increase by another 76 million dollars, according to BEPZA
sources.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Committee of the National Economic Council has
approved two more EPZs in view of the growing interests of
investors in setting up industrial units in EPZs. 
</P>
