<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thais Get Warning to Reduce Water Usage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Metropolitan Waterworks
Authority (MWA) of Thailand will start reducing water volume
released for public consumption by up to 15 percent this month
while officials are kicking off national water-saving campaign to
prepare the country for what is expected to be the worst shortage
in years, The Nation reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ultimate warnings have also been given against Thais' luxurious
water consumption habits, as the reserve in the country's biggest
dam, Bhumibol, has already shrunk to a 35-year low, with the rainy
season still more than half a year away.
</P>
<P>
The Irrigation Department chief Pramote Maiklad, Thursday
repeated his plea for Thais to reduce their water usage by 20 to
30 percent, and complained that authorities' failure to persuade
farmers to reduce second-crop rice cultivation this year is
seriously aggravating the problem.
</P>
<P>
The two dams -- Bhumibol and Sirikit -- now have 3,800 million
cubic meters in reserve, compared to 7,000 to 8,000 million cubic
meters around the same period last year. And the reserves are
dwindling faster than expected.
</P>
<P>
The Irrigation Department had hoped to see second-crop rice
cover 1.9 million rai (304,000 hectares) maximum, but a latest
survey has found the second-crop rice area expanding beyond 2.5
million rai (400.000 hectares).
</P>
<P>
The issue of second-crop rice is sensitive, as it involves poor
farmers. Critics have noted that no firm austerity action has been
taken when it comes to electricity production and tap water
consumption of people in cities. However, the MWA will this month
start reducing water released for public consumption by between
10-15 percent. The reduction, the authority said, would not really
affect Bangkok users if they change their habits which have
resulted in a waste of more than 20 percent of tap water released.
</P>
<P>
At the Bhumibol Dam, strict rules have been introduced to
control the daily release of water. Dam director Kamthon Tikamol
discovered to his dismay Thursday morning that the water level now
stood at 1,386 million cubic meters, compared with 3,314 million
cubic meters the same day last year.
</P>
<P>
People in some provinces have begun to feel the pinch. In
Chiang Mai, northern Thailand, taps have occasionally run dry.
</P>
<P>
Coffee growers in Chumphon province have seen their produce
dwindle by more than 40 percent because of drought. In Khon Kaen
province, about half the province's 2,015 villages are in need of
water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
