<HEADLINE> DPRK Demands U.S. Compensation for Economic Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PONGYANG, JANUARY 8 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) has demanded that the United States pay
compensation for the economic losses caused by its delay in
implementing a 1994 nuclear framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK Anti-Nuclear and Peace Committee issued a statement
on Thursday, saying it had implemented the accord by freezing its
nuclear development program, but the United States had violated
the agreement by building light-water reactors.
</P>
<P>
Due to its delay in implementing the accord, the United States
had caused economic losses valued at tens of billions of dollars
to the country, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
The delay also caused an acute shortage of energy and badly
affected the country's planned economy, it noted.
</P>
<P>
"Thus the United States has the obligation and responsibility
to make compensation for the economic losses," the committee
emphasized in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The committee also attributed the current hardships
experienced by its people to anti-DKPK policies of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, it warned the United States, South Korea and
Japan to abide by the Geneva nuclear agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
