<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German FM: Hungary's Accession to EU Too Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer said here Thursday that it is still too
early to consider a specific timetable for Hungary's entry into
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Following talks with his Hungarian counterpart Martony Janos,
Fischer said Germany hopes that Hungary would be able to enter
the EU as soon as possible. But that also presupposes the EU's
completion of its internal reforms and Hungary's ability to meet
with admission conditions, he added.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said European integration is the only option for
European countries. In the post cold war era, the EU should not
rest its eyes on the West. The EU's eastward expansion is also in
Germany's interests.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU would finalize the earliest date for EU
expansion by the end of the year or the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the accession negotiations with the six countries
aspiring for EU membership, including Hungary, Fischer said
Germany, which assumed the EU presidency in the first half of
1999, would honor its obligations for the implementation of the
EU expansion process.
</P>
<P>
He said that by the end of July, 15 of 31 questions involved
in the negotiations would be put on the agenda. He reiterated
that the precondition for EU expansion is the fulfillment of the
organization's internal reforms.
</P>
<P>
The EU planned to complete its "Agenda 2000" for internal
reforms by the end of March, which the German foreign minister
said would require the related countries to also make certain
concessions.
</P>
<P>
Martony believes the EU would be able to reach agreement on
the Agenda 2000. He said the launch of the single European
currency -- the euro -- would accelerate the elimination of
internal differences, for all differences will manifest
themselves through the euro.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who arrived here Thursday on a one-day visit to
Budapest, also held separate talks with Hungarian President Goncz
Arpad and Prime Minister Orban Viktor.
</P>
<P>
Hungary, in its bid for entry into EU, has repeatedly pledged
that it would meet the criteria for EU accession by 2000 and
hopes that it will become a full EU member in 2002.
</P>
<P>
However, some EU member states, including Germany, oppose a
rush in the expansion drive. They insist that the accession issue
not be raised for deliberations until the completion of EU
internal reforms and the first candidates not be admitted prior
to 2006. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
