<HEADLINE> Corrupt Chinese Official Goes On Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The former deputy mayor of the
city of Guigang in China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has
gone on trial for bribery, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Li Chenglong, 46, was arrested on December 20, 1996 and
accused of taking 3.8 million yuan (457,800 U.S. dollars) in
bribes and accepting goods valued at 6.6 million yuan. In a
2-year investigation, local prosecutors found that, from 1991 to
1996, when Li was the municipal Party committee secretary in
Yulin, he accepted a large number of bribes for the random
appointment of officials and approved various businesses and
illegally sold blocks of land.
</P>
<P>
In one instance, Li appointed the manager of a cement company
to the post of assistant-mayor of Yulin, vice-chairman of its
political consultative conference and deputy director of its
enterprise committee in exchange for 700,000 yuan, prosecutors
say.
</P>
<P>
Other gifts included a jeep, they say. He was also discovered
to have covered for 2 unqualified department-level officials, and
to have illegally approved bank loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
