<HEADLINE> Exiled Bulgarian Monarch Willing to Be Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Exiled Bulgarian king Simeon II
said here Thursday that he is willing to resume his monarchy if
it is necessary.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody understands that I have been brought up to serve my
country and if one day it becomes necessary and if I am strong
enough, I will take up my place," Simeon II said.
</P>
<P>
Simeon II arrived here on December 22 with his wife and his
daughter on a third visit to Bulgaria following his return in
1996 and again in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he would return to Bulgaria for good, Simeon II
said, "If my long-term presence here is useful, not to divide
people, but to find ways to work in harmony with the government
and the authorities, it is good."
</P>
<P>
The royal family was forced to leave Bulgaria after the
eastern European country was declared a republic in 1946
following a referendum during which a majority of Bulgarians
favored the abolishment of the monarchy.
</P>
<P>
The former king said that some of the royal estates could be
used for cultural and environmental purposes and that he planned
more visits to the country in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
