<HEADLINE> Two New Rice Mills to Be Set Up in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government will
spend 100 million rupees (1.5 million U.S. dollars) to establish
two new rice mills to process more rice, the official Daily News
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Cooperative Wholesale Establishment (CWE) S.P.
Chandradasa told the paper that the new mills in Kurunegala and
Anuradhapura districts will be funded by a donor with whom the
government is already in negotiation.
</P>
<P>
Two mills which were set up earlier at Lunugamvehera and
Hingurakgoda in North Central province were funded by the CWE and
have proved a success and can process two metric tons of rice an
hour, said the chairman.
</P>
<P>
Rice imports will be stopped in late January or early February
to accommodate the local paddy harvest, Chandradasa said, adding
that the CWE will effect purchases of the local crop through an
islandwide network of centers.
</P>
<P>
The CWE also has an unprocessed stock of 7000 tons of paddy
which has been purchased from farmers and which will be released
soon to the market, he added. 
