<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai National Carrier Set to Raise Air Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Thai Airways International
(THAI) will raise domestic fares by 13.5-13.7 percent under a
proposal by the Transport and Communications Ministry, aviation
sources said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The fare per flight will go up by about 200 baht (5.5 US
dollars), according to the proposal. But it did not say when.
</P>
<P>
THAI management will work out details and put them to the Civil
Aviation Board for approval, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Communications Minister Suthep Thueksuban has
said THAI domestic flights are cheap compared with those of
Indonesia and Malaysia. The operating cost for the first 100 km is
estimated at six baht/km per passenger but THAI charges passengers
about two baht/km.
</P>
<P>
The fare structure resulted in an annual operating loss of
1.7-2 billion baht (47 million to 55 million dollars), Suthep
said.
</P>
<P>
The carrier is also to cut costs because it cannot raise
domestic fares to break-even level, he said. THAI will have to
deploy aircraft in accordance with traffic demand.
</P>
<P>
Services on loss-making routes would continue until a private
sector operator was ready to take them over, Suthep said.
</P>
<P>
Suthep expected private airlines such as Bangkok Airways,
Orient Thai Airlines and Angel Airlines to raise their domestic
fares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
