<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Returns Military Communications Station to Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. armed forces
Thursday returned a military communications station to the
Panamanian government, the first piece of the canal land to go
back to the Latin American country this year in accordance with
the agreement signed between the two countries in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The Chivo Chivo Station, 21 kilometers north of the Panama
City, used to be the center for the U.S. Southern Command to
transfer military information in the Latin American region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military will also return 115 hectares of barracks --
including the Rodman naval base, the Balboa shooting range, the
Sherman site, the Clayton site and the Howard air base -- will go
back to the Panama government in February.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1997 agreement, the United States is expected to
withdraw all its forces from the canal region by noon on December
31, 1999, and return the Panama Canal to the Panamanian
government.
</P>
<P>
So far, the United States has returned 70 percent of the land
in the canal region to Panama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
