<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Trade Deficit Down 23.2 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's total trade deficit
dropped 23.2 percent to 6.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 from 8.3
billion dollars in 1997, but largely exceeding government
expectation of 4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Development, Industry and Commerce Ministry said Thursday
that exports totalled 51.1 billion dollars and imports amounted
to 57.5 billion dollars last year, dropping by 3.52 percent and
6.2 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In December, the country's trade deficit reached 600 million
dollars, with exports worth 3.9 billion dollars and imports 4.5
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the trade deficit to the country's
economic crisis, adding that its goal was to double exports to
100 billion dollars in 2002.
</P>
<P>
However, economists believe that President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso faces his toughest challenge yet in his plan to slash its
huge budget deficit and shield Brazil from financial meltdown.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 40 billion dollars have flown out of Brazil since last
July for fears that the South American country could not cover
its budget deficit and might default on loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
