<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Greens Arid Zone in Central Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Since 1992, Myanmar has been
implementing a greening and environmental project for the arid
zone in the central part of the country, aimed at systematic
conservation of forests to maintain sustainable yield of forest
products.
</P>
<P>
It initiated the greening projects in nine districts of the
arid zone in Mandalay, Sagaing and Magway divisions in the year
and planted more than 16 million trees including teak and hardwood
trees in areas of over 21,000 hectares, covering 57 townships and
15 mountain ranges between 1994 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
With the formation of a new arid region greening department
under the Ministry of Forestry in June 1997, the project began
expanding up to 13 districts, which includes the establishment of
nurseries, conservation of remaining natural forests, replacement
of fuel wood, restoration of watershed areas and establishment of
water resources.
</P>
<P>
The project covers a total area of 9.14 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
In addition to greening the region, the department also plans
to maintain the ecological system, meet basic requirements for
forest products and carry out socio-economic development for the
rural people.
</P>
<P>
It has also laid down work programs to establish 14,175
hectares of nurseries, conserve 40,500 hectares of natural forests
and plant trees on another area of 40,500 hectares annually.
</P>
<P>
It will also carry out greening projects in the tropical
region, Myingyan district and Mount Popa.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, from 1998 to 2001, the department will carry out
greening and environmental conservation projects in over 1.21
million hectares of reserved forests, over 3.24 million hectares
of non-reserved forests and over 3.64 million hectares of other
cultivated areas.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar promulgated the Forest Law in 1992 to effectively
conserve and preserve the forests which cover about 50 percent of
the total land area.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's forestry rose 1.3
percent in its production in the 1997-98, accounting for 1 percent
of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Of Myanmar's forest products, the production of teak was
283,000 cubic meters, while that of hardwood was 195,694 cubic
meters in the year.
</P>
<P>
The export quantity of the country's teak went to 215,448 cubic
meters, while that of hardwood stood at 142,915 cubic meters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
