<HEADLINE> Decreasing Number Of Criminal Cases In Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The number of criminal cases
in Guangzhou, the capital of China's Guangdong Province, was down
5.2 percent last year, and serious crimes, 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the city has reported a drop of criminal cases in four
years running.
</P>
<P>
The city's public security department cracked down on
robberies and vehicle theft last year and dealt with 2,300 such
cases, which included Cheung Tze-keung's armaments smuggling and
kidnapping activities, a case of stealing of 50 million yuan
worth of stamps, and bank robberies.
</P>
<P>
Public security officers cracked more than 30,000 cases,
18,400 of which were considered serious. They broke up 3,741
criminal gangs, confiscated 112 weapons and money and objects
worth 180 million yuan, and recovered 1,400 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
They also made an effort to crack down on drugs, gambling, and
pornography. In more than 11,000 of these cases, 493.6 kilograms
of heroine seized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
