<HEADLINE> Colombian Rebels Optimistic About Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, COLOMBIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The
leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, on
Thursday expressed optimism about the peace process in the
country before starting their first peace talks with the
government in six years.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic concerning the new peace process, which
starts Thursday, where we will analyze the political, economic,
social, cultural, environmental, and sovereignty situation until
we find solutions," FARC chief Manuel Marulanda said in a
statement read by his representative Thursday for the opening of
the peace talks here.
</P>
<P>
Marulanda, who was scheduled to attend the opening ceremony,
did not appear due allegedly to security reasons.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Marulanda recalled the rebels' fight against
government forces during the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
"The installation of dialogue tables for 90 days -- starting
from the military withdrawal-- to seek with social justice and
sovereignty a way out of the social and armed conflict, which has
been bleeding the country to death for more than four decades,
has prompted great expectations in the country and the world," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The rebel chief said the FARC was ready to hear and be heard,
adding that it would notify the news media of the results of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to drug-trafficking, Marulanda said, "It is
necessary that the powers make plans to eradicate coca and opium
poppy crops."
</P>
<P>
He said the planting of illegal crops by poor Colombian
farmers had deep, economic and social roots, and "should not be
treated in a repressive way."
</P>
<P>
Marulanda said he favored a more just society to end the
causes of violence.
</P>
<P>
The rebels will meet with the government in the Venezuelan
capital of Caracas and in the Mexican city of Tlaxcala, he said,
adding that this "proved FARC's political will to seek a
political solution to the conflict."
</P>
<P>
Marulanda called on all Colombians to strengthen their unity
around the 10-point rebel communique, which he said was the basis
for a political solution and for Colombia's reconciliation and
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Marulanda's conditions for peace include the dismantling of
right-wing paramilitary groups and the exchange of 252 jailed
rebels for more than 350 police and soldiers captured since 1996.
He also seeks a redistribution of wealth in the long term.
</P>
</TEXT>
