<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast China Has Warm Winter This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, January 8 (Xinhua) -- It is a sight rarely seen in
winter on the streets of Fuzhou in eastern China's Fujian
Province: young women still wearing skirts and young men in shirt
sleeves.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Zhou, a shop assistant, is walking with goods on his
shoulder, and says,"I don't feel cold at all though I am just
wearing a shirt. I would usually be wearing a worn woolen sweater
at this time of the year."
</P>
<P>
Mr.Liu, who is 70 years old, said that he has never seen such
a warm winter in Fuzhou since he moved to the city over 40 years
ago. "I would have put on a woolen sweater and even a coat at
this time before, but now I only have my woolen vest on."
</P>
<P>
It was widely believed earlier last year that it would be cold
this winter since the winters of the past several years were
warm. However, the reality is just the opposite, and it has been
as high as 19 and 20 degrees Centigrade during the past ten days
or so, quite a bit warmer than usual for winter here.
</P>
<P>
Song Dezhong, senior engineer with the Fujian Provincial
Meteorological Center, explained that the global warming is part
of the reason for the warm winter in Fuzhou. On the other hand,
the strong latitude circulation and the comparatively weak radial
circulation in the westerly belt this year has also played a part
in producing the abnormal temperatures, and a decrease in the
force of the cold air masses moving southward, and their
frequency, have also contributed to the warming trend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
