<HEADLINE> Fog Blocks Traffic In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The residents of the city of
Shanghai are being harassed by mosquitoes these warm winter days,
but what is worse, the fog caused by the unusually warm winter
has created many unexpected traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
The East China Air Traffic Control Bureau reports that there
have been at least a dozen days of dense fog in Shanghai since
December. In normal years, it usually gets only 3 or 4.
</P>
<P>
The highest temperature was between 13 and 16 degrees C. and
the lowest was around 1 or 2 degrees.
</P>
<P>
Visibility at the city's Hongqiao Airport was only 50 meters at
times, delaying about 40 flights on those days. On January 2, it
even stopped 159 flights and stranded 10,000 passengers, Gu
Xiaoguang, an airport spokesman reports.
</P>
<P>
Expressways linking Shanghai with the cities of Hangzhou,
Nanjing and Jiaxing have been closed several times because of the
dense fog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
