<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces After-School Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Thursday that he hoped to devote 600 million U.S. dollars to
creating programs that would give thousands of American children
activities to do after school.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, the latest from Clinton's fiscal 2000 budget,
calls for three times the amount of money the federal government
now devotes to after-school programs. Clinton tied eligibility
for the program to his effort to halt "social promotions" that
move children up in the next grade even if they did not grasp
their lessons in the previous one.
</P>
<P>
"Our public schools must change," Clinton said. "Don't flunk
anybody because the system is failing the kids. Give them the
after-school programs. Give them the summer school programs. Give
them the tools they need to succeed."
</P>
<P>
Clinton unveiled the proposal in a ceremony in the White House
with the participation of his wife, Hillary, and Vice-President
Al Gore. It is among several policy initiatives that Clinton will
offer in his State of the Union address on January 19.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the budget he will send to Congress next month
will call for tripling the amount spent on the 21st Century
Learning Center Program, which provides public schools with money
for educational and recreational programs in the afternoon hours
when school is out but most working parents are still at their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
That program, currently funded at 200 million dollars, serves
190,000 children at 800 schools in 46 states and the District of
Columbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Newspaper Warns Overseas Investors of Mistakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese economic
newspaper has advised overseas investors to use world advanced
technology, adapt themselves to market changes, study the
regional differences in China's markets and hire first-class
management personnel to prevent losses when running businesses in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The China Economic Times said that although overseas ventures
in China may have great opportunities for being successful, some
have actually suffered losses due to making mistakes.
</P>
<P>
It cited examples in Shanghai where 47.35 percent of
overseas-invested companies reported losses in 1998. Overall
losses reached 3.9 billion yuan (about 488 million U.S. dollars).
Even four world famous ventures each reported a loss of more than
100 million yuan (about 12.5 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"China's market is not what it used to be when the policy of
opening and reform first began," the business newspaper stressed.
"It is now requires the most advanced technological skills and is
more dynamic with lower prices creating fierce competition."
</P>
<P>
Products made with the world's most advanced technologies will
have more competitive advantages as the level of China's
technology is being upgraded very rapidly, and overseas investors
should constantly upgrade their products to meet the demands of
this fast changing market, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the newspaper said some investors have ignored
the huge regional differences in China.
</P>
<P>
"It would be very dangerous to use just one market strategy in
China," it said. "People in different parts of China have
different needs and business modes. The infrastructure conditions
and the role of government also vary from region to region."
</P>
<P>
Some companies operating at a loss had appointed managers
close to retiring age to run their firms, appointed inexperienced
'greenhorns' or people with little knowledge about China and its
language. They were thus unable to make contacts at the right
level with either superiors or local employees, the newspaper
declared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
