<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teenager Hacker Breaks Into Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Police in north China's Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region recently caught a computer hacker who
illegally accessed a local information service network.
</P>
<P>
The hacker, a 13-year-old middle school student, connected to
the local 169 information service network in the name of his
father and opened a main page called "Hacker" free of charge at
the website of Guangzhou in early October last year.
</P>
<P>
Later he entered a mail server by decoding, sent the "Hacker"
mainpage to a catalog in the mail server, and changed the codes,
thereby becoming able to control the work account of the managers
of the multi-media telecommunication system of Hohhot, capital of
the region.
</P>
<P>
The middle school student also threatened to turn the mainpage
of the 169 information service network into a hackers mainpage in
three days.
</P>
<P>
What the teenager did violated Chinese law but he was immune
to any legal action as he has not reached the age of 14. The
police ordered the parents to try and keep a closer watch on him
and encourage education on him.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
