<HEADLINE> Philippines Issues 1 Billion Dollars of Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
successfully launched 1 billion U.S. dollars of global bonds in
the international debt markets Thursday, reflecting the return of
investor confidence in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Journal Friday quoted Finance Secretary Edgardo
Espiritu as saying that the government's 750 million dollar bond
offering in the U.S. market drew subscriptions totaling 2.5
billion dollars, or three times more than the package.
</P>
<P>
The response of the international market to the Philippine bond
proves the return of investor confidence in the Philippines, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The 1 billion dollars of bonds was bigger than the 750 million
dollars the market had been expecting, and was equally split into
two tranches. The first was an increase to the Philippines'
existing April 2008 bond, while the second was a new 20-year bond.
</P>
<P>
The bond was priced by lead managers J.P. Morgan, Morgan
Stanley Dean Witer and Warburg Dillon Read during New York trading
Thursday, local newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
The deal was the first from a Southeast Asian country since the
start of the Asian crisis, and fueled the hope that other Asian
borrowers may soon be able to raise funds in the market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
