<HEADLINE> Germany, Czech Pledge Enhances Bilateral Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting German Foreign Minister
Joschka Fischer and his Czech counterpart Jan Kavan said here
Thursday that the two countries should further strengthen their
bilateral links and bring traditional cooperation to a new level.
</P>
<P>
No outstanding issues exist between the two countries, the two
officials told reporters after the meeting. They said their
countries are currently enjoying good political relationships and
economic and trade cooperation is moving along smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Fischer reiterated that Germany, which took over the rotating
European Union (EU) presidency on January 1, supports the Czech
Republic's efforts to join the EU. The Czech Republic and five
other countries -- Poland, Hungary, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus
-- started EU membership negotiations last November.
</P>
<P>
Fischer arrived here Wednesday for a two-day visit, during
which he also met with Czech Prime Minister Milos Zeman and
Chairman of the Chamber of Deputies (Lower House) Vaclav Klaus.
The two sides agreed that Zeman will pay a visit to Germany in
March.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries have been developing an overall
relationship during the past several years, especially after the
signing of a joint declaration of reconciliation in January 1997
to solve historical issues and to normalize bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, Germany has replaced the former Soviet
Union as the largest trading partner of the Czech Republic,
accounting for as much as 36 percent of its foreign trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
