<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia's Peace Talks Snubbed by Absence of Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, COLOMBIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The
peace pledge of Colombian President Andres Pastrana on Thursday
was snubbed by a top rebel leader's absence from talks which may
have ended a 50-year conflict that claims thousands of lives eve
ry year.
</P>
<P>
"The time for peace has arrived and nothing will be able to
detain it. I have come to San Vicente del Caguan as the head of
state to keep my word," said President Pastrana, sitting alone
beside an empty seat reserved for Manuel Marulanda, the founder
of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), who has not
been seen in public in decades.
</P>
<P>
"Manuel Marulanda Velez' absence is no reason not to go ahead
with the installation of a dialogue table and the setting of an
agenda of talks leading toward peace," said Pastrana, who later
declared the formal opening of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, speaking on the RNC TV network, rebel commander
Raul Reyes said Marulanda could not come due to unspecified
"threats against his life."
</P>
<P>
So far, the parties have not yet set an agenda and the FARC is
at its strongest ever with over 15,000 men who control about 40
percent of the countryside.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana's statement was made after a rebel commander, Joaquin
Gomez, spoke in Marulanda's place, reading an angry speech
blasting years of alleged government duplicity in past peace
proposals.
</P>
<P>
The speech, signed by Marulanda, also slammed Pastrana for
creating what the rebel head said were new counter-guerrilla
battalions with U.S. anti-drug aid totaling 290 million U.S.
dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
More than five months ago, Pastrana went to Marulanda's jungle
hideout to push the third government attempt to reach peace with
the FARC after failed efforts at the start of 1980's and the
1990's.
</P>
<P>
Marulanda's conditions for peace include dismantling
pro-government paramilitary groups and the exchange of over 250
jailed rebels for more than 350 police and soldiers captured
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The rebels who have refused a cease-fire or any other
concessions, plan to implement sweeping agrarian reforms, radical
wealth redistribution and an end to free-market economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The FARC is being accused by Washington and the Colombian
government of using funds from the drug trade to finance their
operations. The rebels are believed to earn over 790 million
dollars a year from drug trafficking, kidnapping and extortion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taihu's Water Quality Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 8 (Xinhua) -- Central and local governments
will not relax efforts to clean up the nation's third-largest
freshwater lake, even though major industries are no longer
discharging excessive pollutants into the Taihu Lake.
</P>
<P>
A majority of enterprises required to meet stricter national
environmental standards before January 1 completed their
pollution-control projects, meeting the country's goal, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Random inspections during the past week revealed all pollu
tion-control equipment were functioning well, and no covert
discharging was happening, the paper quoted an official with the
State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA) as saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of the 770 enterprises ordered to improve
their environmental protection facilities completed treatment
projects, Huang Youzhang, with the Jiangsu Provincial
Environmental Protection Bureau, said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government vows to monitor enterprises'
discharges, and violators will either be fined or closed down
until they improve their facilities, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province is undertaking similar measures to restrict
the amount of pollution discharged into the lake, notes
provincial official Shi Jianrong.
</P>
<P>
Taihu's water quality is better than it was this time last
year, Shi said, adding however, more must be done, including
construction of additional treatment plants.
</P>
<P>
The central government is planning a regional meeting this
month to outline experiences during the first-phase of the lake's
cleanup, notes Qiao zhiqi, SEPA's director of pollution control.
</P>
<P>
These experiences could be used as a basis for treating other
bodies of water in China, Qiao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
