<HEADLINE> 500 Economists Expected for Economic Conference In Havana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Around 500 economists from 48
countries are expected to attend a meeting on globalization and
development problems scheduled for January 18-22 in Havana.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban president of the Latin American Economists
Association, Roberto Verrier, who also heads the meeting's
organizing committee, said Thursday that 15 world organizations
would send representatives to the event.
</P>
<P>
They include the United Nations, the World Trade Organization
(WTO), the Latin American Integration Association (LAIA) or
(ALADI) in Spanish, the Economic Commission for Latin America,
the World Bank and the InterAmerican Development Bank (IDB).
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also be attended by delegates from the Group
of 77, and the Latin American Economic System.
</P>
<P>
On top of the meeting's agenda are the issues of social impact
of globalization, prospects and players in the world's economic
future, and current world trade systems.
</P>
<P>
The conclusions reached on the issues by the participants will
be sent to international agencies and foreign governments to seek
possible solutions. 
</P>
