<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obligatory Schooling for Migrants' Children in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, January 8 (Xinhua) -- As ten-year-old Zhang Lili was
reading her textbooks in a primary school in Anhui Province in
east China, no one could have imagined that only five months ago
she had left school in her home in the coastal province of Zheji
ang because she had traveled with her parents who were working in
Anhui.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's parents are among China's increasing number of
migrants to urban areas due to the ongoing establishment of a
market economy.
</P>
<P>
These migrants find it hard to register their children in a
local school because of China's residence registration
regulations. If these temporary students, all without
registration cards, are pouring into local schools, the teaching
staff are unable to cope.
</P>
<P>
This social problem was brought to the government's attention
and a new regulation was issued early last year by the Ministry
of Education and the Ministry of Public Security, requiring local
governments to guarantee education for migrants' children aged
between 6 and 14 and who have lived for more than six months in
the area.
</P>
<P>
The city of Hefei, for instance, has thus solved the schooling
problem for 6,000 children like Zhang, which represents more than
90 percent of the total number in the region.
</P>
<P>
The two cities of Shanghai and Shenzhen, located in the east
and south of China, have the largest number of migrants, with
children in need of education totalling 14,000 and 110,000
respectively. Now, many private schools have been set up to ease
the pressure on the government. Twenty-five schools, handling
14,000 migrant children, have been opened in Shenzhen, where the
number of "outsiders" has reached 2.7 million, some 70 percent of
the city's total population.
</P>
<P>
But the pressure remains, with an imbalance between the
increasing number of migrants across China and the limited number
of schools available for their children. An official in Anhui's
provincial educational sector said that a cross-regional
educational network should be set up to tackle the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Ratifies Deal, Promises Fan-Friendly League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The NBA on Thursday revealed
plans to become more fan-friendly as its Board of Governors
unanimously ratified the new six-year collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
While remaining vague about some of the particulars of the
deal-- which still is about a week to 10 days from being
formalized -- NBA commissioner David Stern and deputy
commissioner Russ Granik announced teams would have open workouts
and marquee TV games would remain on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
The league will have a schedule of approximately 50 games per
team that likely will begin February 5, with each team playing
about five of six games out of conference. The playoffs will
remain the same 16-team format and will begin approximately May
1, running to the last week in June.
</P>
<P>
Stern said each team will have open workouts, play a pair of
fan-friendly exhibition games and offer discounted tickets of $10
by next season at the latest.
</P>
<P>
"There are many people who say the proof will be in the
pudding and the surveys we have say there are many fans who will
remain NBA fans," Stern said. "We are comfortable that if we work
hard, our fans will give us the opportunity to redeem ourselves."
</P>
<P>
"We owe a lot of our fans, and we plan to work with our
players and the NBA to win back the fans' loyalty and trust,"
union executive director Billy Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
One day after the union voted overwhelmingly for the
late-night deal struck by Stern and Hunter, owners voted 29-0 to
ratify the deal.
</P>
<P>
"We're extremely pleased that we have a ratified agreement
with the union," said Stern, who was joined at a news conference
at a midtown hotel by Granik and Hunter.
</P>
<P>
The lockout will not officially end until the agreement has
been finalized, but team facilities will open to players and trai
ners Monday and training camps will officially open no later than
January 18.
</P>
<P>
"It's definitely going to favor either the players or the
teams," Stern said. "I'm sure it is going to be a mad scramble.
These things have a way of working themselves out. It will
probably be combination in different cities."
</P>
<P>
With each team playing 50 games over a period of less than
three months, teams will be forced to play on three consecutive
nights on occasion. The league will average more than eight games
per night.
</P>
<P>
In order to placate NBC and Turner, which paid $23 million to
each team this season as part of their telecast agreement with
the league, some marquee interconference matchups will be
retained.
</P>
<P>
"If teams have to play three in a row, I don't think that is
intolerable," Granik said. "There will some interconference
games, but a team from the East will only play five or six teams
from the West and vice versa."
</P>
<P>
Stern indicated that there would be at least one game on TNT
on February 5 and a doubleheader on February 7 on NBC.
</P>
<P>
"Our broadcast partners are more interested in rescheduling
than they are about money," Stern said. "We anticipate we will
add games to both NBC and TNT. On NBC, it probably be done if we
extend the regular season.
</P>
<P>
"On TNT and TBS, we will look for key matchups and add
additional games along the way. Everything is on the table."
</P>
<P>
Stern also revealed: "Starting next year, we will assure that
fans are getting a chance to attend games for $10," he said. "We
are not going to charge for exhibition games. We will also open
up at least one scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
"We are painfully aware of the beating that professional
athletes and teams have taken at the hands of the public. We have
talked about changing the paradigm. We have talked to teams about
understanding the history and what is going on. This is the next
step in that process. I ask you to judge us in a year." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
