<HEADLINE> Colombian Peace Talks Start Without Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, COLOMBIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The
peace talks in Colombia started on Thursday without the presence
of the top rebel leader Manuel Marulanda.
</P>
<P>
Marulanda, the founder of the hemisphere's most powerful rebel
group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, was
scheduled to have a historical encounter with President Andres
Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana returned to the capital of Bogota immediately after
the one-hour ceremony when he waited in vain for Manuel Marulanda.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks were expected to end 50 years of civil war
which claims thousands of casualties every year.
</P>
<P>
After Pastrana formally declared the talks open, High
Commissioner for Peace Victor Ricardo read a joint
government-rebel communique.
</P>
<P>
The three-point statement said there was a will to reach a
political solution to the problems between the two parties,
announcing a prompt start of the peace negotiations and pledging
social justice for all Colombians. 
</P>
