<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100GMT, January 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA -- At least 40 people are feared dead when the boat
they were traveling in capsized near a fish landing site at Lake
Albert in western Uganda on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The incident became known Thursday morning, Radio Uganda
reported Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the accounts of the 12 survivors, the boat was
overloaded with fish and people. (Uganda-Boat Accident)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece Thursday criticized neighboring Turkey for
the latter's attack on Athens regarding the issue of Athens
Flight Information Region (FIR).
</P>
<P>
Greece said that Turkey's aim was to change the status quo of
air traffic control in the Aegean Sea and to create problems in
relations between the two countries. (Greece-Turkey)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African President Nelson Mandela and
British Prime Minister Tony Blair Thursday reported progress in
talks about the pending trial of two Libyans suspected of
involvement in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing.
</P>
<P>
After meeting at Mandela's Pretoria residence, the two
leaders told reporters that they had made headway on the
outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Blair declined to reveal details of their
discussions. (SAfrica-Britain-Leaders)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- The euro continued to fall against the dollar and the
European Central Bank announced a reference rate for Thursday of
1.1632 dollars, more than a cent lower than the 1.1743 dollars on
the previous day.
</P>
<P>
The euro fell against other currencies too, with rates set at
0.70585 pounds after 0.70760 pounds and 129.43 yen after 131.42
yen Wednesday. But the euro was up against the Swiss franc at
1.6165 after 1.6116 Wednesday. (Germany-Euro-Shares)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate started impeachment trial
against President Bill Clinton on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
On December 19 last year, the U.S. House of Representatives
passed on largely party-line votes two articles of impeachment
against Clinton alleging he committed perjury and obstructed
justice in trying to cover up his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, a White House intern. (US-Impeachment)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A U.S. Air Force F-16 jet fighter fired a
high-speed anti-radar missile at an air-defense radar site in
northern Iraq on Thursday after the pilot determined he was about
to be fired on by a surface-to-air missile, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The attack, taking place at about 11:15 a.m. Iraqi time (0815
GMT), was to "prevent any offensive fire" from the Iraqi
air-defense installation, according to a statement issued by U.S.
European Command, the U.S. headquarters for Air Force planes
involved in enforcing a no-fly zone over northern Iraq.
(US-Iraq-Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON-- U.S. President Bill Clinton will ask Congress to
approve about 7 billion U.S. dollars over the next six years to
develop a limited U.S. defense against ballistic missiles, New
York Times quoted administration officials as saying on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the funds would be sought next month
as part of the proposed fiscal year 2000 defense budget, but that
Clinton was unlikely to decide on any deployment of the system
until at least June 2000. (US-Missile) 
</P>
