<HEADLINE> Governor Rule in Sindh Province to Continue: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said Thursday the governor's rule in Sindh province will
continue till the objectives are achieved and law and order
situation is improved there.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said his government is determined to
eliminate terrorism from the southern port city and commercial
center of Karachi, and the military courts have been established
to provide speedy justice.
</P>
<P>
Sharif made these remarks during an informal chat with a group
of Islamabad-based journalists at the prime minister's house,
according to a report by the Associated Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
About the governor's rule imposed at the end of October last
year, Sharif said that the action had become imperative because
terrorists had made Karachi hostage, crippled the national economy
and killed innocent people as well as those who had rendered
invaluable services to the nation.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that after the establishment of the military courts
in Karachi in mid November 1998, terrorists were being punished
for the first time. The government will not come under pressure
from any quarters regarding operation against the terrorists, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the prime minister, the cases of those already
involved in terrorism, land-grabbing, extortion, murders, and
terrorism are being transferred to the military courts after
thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said that his government's focus was to
restore normalcy in Karachi and confidence of the investors to
improve economic condition of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
