<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus Service Not to Help Improve Pak-India Ties: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz said that a proposed bus service between Pakistan and
India means to provide relief to visitors and should not be taken
as a measure to enhance bilateral ties with India.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen at a local function in honor of Muslim
diplomats in Pakistan Thursday night, Aziz said "Kashmir solution
is the only key to put Pakistan-India bilateral ties on track."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Kashmir policy would not be changed at any
cost and relations with India would not normalize till the
settlement of the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that reciprocal or unilateral releasing Indian
fishermen from Pakistani jails should also not be taken as a
measure to improve ties with New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
"This is a human issue and we do not believe to keep these poor
fellows for years and years in the jails on violating the
country's sea boundaries", he said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has not shift in its foreign policy as far as India
is concerned but exchange of views or measures like bus service,
fishermen or trade are confidence building measures to resolve
differences, especially the core issue of Kashmir with India," he
noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
