<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Helps Central American Countries Overcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Thursday that it
will provide 8 million Canadian dollars(5.28 million U.S.dollars)
to help central American countries affected by Hurricane Mitch
last year to make payments on their international debts.
</P>
<P>
The contribution will be made to the World Bank Central America
Emergency Trust Fund (CAETF), which has been established to help
Honduras, Nicaragua, Guatemala and El Salvador pay their debts to
international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's contribution to this Trust Fund will enable these
governments to use more of their own funds to rebuild their
countries, which were shattered by Hurricane Mitch," said
International Cooperation Minister Diane Marleau in a release.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Mitch has destroyed significant agricultural
production, which will severely reduce export earnings in 1999 and
beyond for these countries. At the same time, they are facing
considerable import needs for reconstruction and to meet the
demand for food, medicines and fuel, said the release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
