<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blue-Chips Mixed at New York Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chips at the New York
Stock Exchanges were mixed Thursday. The dow Jones industrial
average and the Standard &AMP; Pool's 500 Index lowered slightly while
Nasdaq rose a bit.
</P>
<P>
The Dow slid in the morning and dropped 86.51 at 9,458.46 in
early afternoon from the record closing high of 9,544.97
Wednesday. But the Dow closed at 9,537.76 with a loss of only 7.21
points because of a last-minute rally partially fueled by bank
shares.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's early fall was driven by a recommendation given by
the well-know market analist Abby Joseph Cohen of Goldman Sachs
that investors trim their stock investments.
</P>
<P>
Cohen suggested this morning that investors trim the equities
portion of their portfolios by 2 percent to 70 percent from 72
percent and at the same time add to their bond investments because
stocks, she said, were overvalued.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index was also down 2.61 at 1,269.73
in the close of trading. But the technology-heavy Nasdaq was up
5.23 at 2,326.09 and American Stock Exchange Index rose 2.51 at
703.98 as well.
</P>
<P>
The other reason for the slump in a number of blue-chips was
Brazil's economic trouble. Minas gerais, the third-wealthiest
state of the Latin American country, declared a 90-day moratorium
on federal debt payment Wednesday. The news dampened enthusiasm of
the U.S. investors because Brazil is an important importer of U.S.
goods.
</P>
<P>
The bad news from Brazil also drove U.S. dollar down against
most currencies. In late trading at the New York Foreign
Exchanges, the European single currency, euro, was quoted at
1.1670 U.S. dollars, up from 1.1592 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 111.04 Japanese yen late Thursday,
down from 112.66 yen. The British pound was quoted at 1.6513
dollars, down from 1.6556 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
