<HEADLINE> UK Presses for WTO Resolution of Banana Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom government
said on Thursday that it was pressing the World Trade Organization
(WTO) for a resolution of the banana dispute between the European
Union (EU) and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Trade and Industry (DTI) said in a statement
that the European Union, supported by Britain, will next week
request that the WTO examine the EU's own revised banana import
regime to establish definitively whether it breaks WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
"The British government's efforts... are directed towards
having the whole issue of banana imports referred back to the
proper adjudication process within the World Trade Organization,"
British Trade Minister Brian Wilson said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
A key WTO meeting on the dispute is scheduled for January 12.
Latin American and Carribean countries will also be involved in
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The United States accuses the EU of failing to comply with a
1997 WTO ruling which found its banana import policy favored
former colonies in the Caribbean at the expense of Latin American
producers and U.S. marketing companies.
</P>
<P>
Washington says the new EU regime is little changed and still
does not conform to WTO rules, and has announced it will impose
massive tariffs on a range of EU goods from March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
