<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest U.S. Bank Offers Fingerprint Access to Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Bank of America, the largest
bank in the United States, has initiated a fingerprint-based smart
card biometric program to give individuals access to their online
banking services.
</P>
<P>
"Biometric technology is becoming increasingly accessible, and
we believe it will play a growing role in security and
authentication for financial products, services and transactions
in the new millenium," the bank said in a statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Before using the system, the bank stores a customer's online
banking login, passcode and fingerprint on the chip attached to a
multi-application smart card. The customer then follows a
customary login process to access banking information over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
The biometric security authentication is completed when the
customer places a finger on a small scanning device attached to a
personal computer. The software matches it against the image
already stored on the smart card's chip. Finally the customer gets
onto the the web page for the bank's PC Load smart card program,
from where he can transfer value from his checking account onto
the Visa Cash stored value application on his smart card.
</P>
<P>
The bank first started testing smart cards more than four years
ago and has a special group that explores new ways to utilize the
technology. Out of that group has come the first multi-application
smart card program utilizing Visa Cash and non-finance features
and the first PC program for Visa Cash stored-value chip cards.
The group has also deployed a variety of smart-card programs for
companies and public facilities across the country.
</P>
<P>
"Biometric technology -- coupled with smart cards -- has the
potential to take security, convenience and versatility to another
level for our customers," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Bank of America now provides financial products and services to
30 million households and two million businesses in the United
States. More than one million of the bank's customers bank online
via the Internet, America Online or personal financial management
software. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
