<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECB's Interest Rates Remain Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN January 7 (Xinhua) -- President of the European Central
Bank (ECB) Wim Duisenberg said Thursday evening that ECB left the
interest rates unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"I see no tendency that could force us to change interest rates
in the near future," Duisenberg said after the first board meeting
of the ECB since the single European currency was launched on
January 1.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the latest round of interest cuts by
European central banks prior to the launch of the single currency,
the euro, had left no more scope for further rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
The ECB last month set the key interest rate for Euroland at 3
per cent. The ECB also announced that as a transitory measure, the
deposit rate will be initially set at 2.75 percent and the
marginal lending rate at 3.25 per cent.
</P>
<P>
As of 21 January, the rates for these lending facilities will
be set at 2 percent and 4.5 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Duisenberg said that the launch of the euro era had proceeded
smoothly in the financial sector and was "to our satisfaction".
</P>
</TEXT>
