<HEADLINE> U.S. Demands Iraq to Let UNSCOM Back for Arms Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein should allow U.N.
weapons inspectors back for their mission before sanctions against
Iraq could be considered.
</P>
<P>
"it's Mr Saddam Hussein who wants to have sanctions lifted, and
he's not going to have sanctions lifted if UNSCOM isn't able to go
in there, do its job, and come out and certify that Iraq has been
disarmed," State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has refused to let UNSCOM, responsible for destroying
weapons of mass destruction in Iraq under U.N. resolutions, back
in its present form after U.S. and British Bombing raid in
December 16-19 on its defense and security sites, thus leaving the
future of the weapons inspection system in limbo.
</P>
<P>
"We can live with the status quo. It's not perfect. We would
like to see an effective UNSCOM going back in there but we're not
panting to have it go back," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Republican Representative Porter Goss, chairman of
the House Intelligence Committee, has asked CIA Director George
Tenet to appear some time this month at testify in a unusual
public hearing on the effect of the U.S. air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a letter, released on Thursday, Goss posed three pages of
questions, saying he wanted to know if the four-day air strikes
weakened or strengthened Saddam Hussein's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
Another question was what U.S. intelligence could do to support
the administration's goal of "dismantling the Iraqi regime."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
