<HEADLINE> S. Leone Warring Sides Agree on Cease-Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Ahmad Tejan
Kabbah said Thursday that he had reached a cease-fire agreement with rebel
leaders, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in capital Freetown, Kabbah said that both
parties had ordered an immediate cease-fire in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
If conditions were met for seven days, the statement noted, he would
authorize the release of rebel leader Foday Sankoh, who was sentenced to
death for supporting the coup which ousted Kabbah in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah told a press conference held at Freetown's Lungi airport that he
and Sankoh had agreed to implement an accord signed in 1996 in Cote d'Voire
on ending the civil conflicts in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Sierra Leonean Finance Minister James Jonah conceded
that the rebels controlled parts of Freetown's eastern and central sections.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that the west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG was
in control of all "major strategic points" in the capital city and
maintained that the rebels never made a "dent in the western area."
</P>
<P>
An ECOMOG spokesman also said that "we are still maintaining our
position ensuring perfect security within Freetown." 
</P>
</TEXT>
