<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Companies Vie to Tap Romanian Oil Market Niches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign oil companies, running
neck and neck with Petrom national company of Romania, are poised
to extend the network of their petrol stations in the territory.
</P>
<P>
According to a Thursday report the fuel chain currently owning
66 petrol stations in Romania, thinks big, aiming at places that
so far have been out of its reach.
</P>
<P>
Shell routinely invests more than a million US dollars in the
construction of one petrol station. Notwithstanding its relatively
high prices compared to other operators', the company's sales have
reportedly gone up, given the good-reputed quality of the
products.
</P>
<P>
Mol company for its part announced intention to set in place 12
petrol stations in the country. The company will also build up two
terminals for fuel loading.
</P>
<P>
Mol executives said the investment would amount to 17 million
US dollars. So far they said the company has poured 25.9 million
US dollars in Romania and expected to bring in more than 80
million by the year 2002, enough for adding 80 new stations to
company's current distribution array.
</P>
<P>
Lukoil is optimistic after its designers completed a 40 petrol
stations blueprint, due to be implemented in 1999. Lukoil has set
sight on the Petrotel refinery, 60 km north of Bucharest, which it
said would endow with modern oil processing equipment.
</P>
<P>
Lukoil wants to boost the kerosen production capacity in an
attempt to give Romania the upper-hand among the fuel suppliers of
aviation companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
