<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House: Trial of Clinton Could be "Manifestly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The impeachment trial of
President Bill Clinton in the Senate threatened to be "manifestly
unfair" by opening without clear rules on how it will proceed,
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We may be in a situation where we do move forward without
clear rules of the road," Lockhart said. "I would suggest that
that would be a situation, an environment, that is manifestly
unfair to the president."
</P>
<P>
Lockhart spoke just minutes after U.S. Chief Justice William
Rehnquist was sworn in to preside over the trial.
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist's action marks the official opening of the Senate
trial in which the 100-member body will serve as jurors, sworn by
Rehnquist to an oath of impartiality.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in the U.S. since the trial of Andrew
Johnson in 1868 that senators were asked to try a president.
</P>
<P>
On December 19 last year, the U.S. House of Representatives
passed on largely party-line votes two articles of impeachment
against Clinton alleging he committed perjury and obstructed
justice in trying to cover up his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
The votes sent the issue to the Senate, where a two-thirds
majority must vote to convict Clinton in order to remove him from
office.
</P>
<P>
The Senate had yet to make major decisions on how to proceed
with the case, and whether to permit witnesses. Senate Republicans
said votes could be held later on Thursday on Democratic and
Republican proposals for trial procedures, with the trial itself
resuming next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The White House's expression of concern was its most explicit
challenge to the Senate's conduct of the trial. It marked a
departure from the deference the White House has shown to the
Senate because of its broad authority in determining how the trial
is run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Iraq's Basra Oil Refinery under Repairing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that Iraq was repairing its oil refinery at Basra damaged
in December's air raid by U.S. missiles, and it would be back in
operation in a month or two.
</P>
<P>
"They are trying to repair that," said Anthony Zinni, commander
of the U.S. Central Command responsible for the December 16-19
bombing raid against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We had not thought we would take it out permanently. I think
over a period of time they will get it back up. I estimate a month
or two," he told a news conference at the Foreign Press Club.
</P>
<P>
He said the attack on the Basra facility was aimed at
interrupting the illegal smuggling of gas oil.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen said previously that Iraq used
the Basra facility to process and smuggle oil in violation of the
U.N. program that allows the country to export up to 5.256
billion U.S. dollars oil every six months for food and medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
