<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo(K) Calls on Security Council to Denounce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior diplomat from
Congo(K) on Thursday called upon the U.N. Security Council to
denounce invasions of Rwanda and Uganda into his country and to
ask both of the countries to immediately pull their troops out of
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Andre Kapanga, permanent representative of Congo(K) to the
United Nations, told a press conference that "The silence of the
Security Council on this issue has encouraged the two invading
countries in their obstinacy to occupy Congolese territory."
</P>
<P>
"This occupation certainly has its price," he said, citing "a
systematic pillage of Congolese minerals in occupied territories,
a destruction of the Congolese rain forest whose timber is
methodically being sent to Uganda en masse, and the killing of
innocent civilians throughout the areas occupied by the Rwandan
and Ugandan forces."
</P>
<P>
"My Government has repeatedly asked the United Nations Security
Council to vigorously condemn both Rwanda and Uganda for violating
the territorial integrity of the Democratic Republic of the Congo,
to ask both Rwanda and Uganda to immediately withdraw their troops
from the Congolese territory, to put an end to the violation of
the human rights of the Congolese people who are under the
territory they are occupying," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kapanga wrote a letter to the Security Council, but he
complained the council is yet to make any response, saying that
the Security Council, in charge of peace and security in the world
under the U.N. Charter, should pay real attention to the conflicts
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Congolese envoy accused both Rwanda and Uganda
of their refusal to participate in regional peace efforts, saying
that the two countries are not interested in peace, "what they are
interested in is the minerals of the Congo, and timber of the
Congo."
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda first denied their involvement in the
conflicts of Congo (K), but three months after the war started in
August last year in eastern Congo (K), "both Rwanda and Uganda
acknowledged their direct involvement in the war since its
beginning," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi-led forces, backed by Rwanda and Uganda, rose up in
August last year in the eastern part of the country to topple the
government headed by President Laurent Kabila, who came to power
in May 1997 after a military campaign across the country, then
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Kapanga also asked the United Nations and the Security Council
to investigate the massacre of about 500 civilians in Makobola,
east Congo (K). Before long, Angola, Namibia and Zambia sent their
troops into Congo (K) to fight along with President Kabila against
rebels.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who had read reports of the
alleged massacre with deep concerns, on Wednesday issued a
statement, voicing his "strong condemnation" of the mass killing
in the African country.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General believes there can be no military
solution to the conflict," the statement said, "He will continue
to actively support current regional efforts to broker a
ceasefire, the withdrawal of foreign troops from the territory of
the DRC, and a broadening of the democratic space in the country,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
The massacre, if confirmed, will appear to be the largest mass
killing since the start of the August 1998 rebellion. Those
killings, never fully investigated, had their roots in the
region's bitter ethnic conflict between the Tutsi and Hutu, and in
the massacre of more than half a million Tutsi in Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Government Approves Police Draft Statute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Government on
Thursday approved a draft statute for the country's Police forces,
aiming to demilitarize the Police and consecrate them as a public
service department.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft, the policemen will be civil servants on
special statutes who, given the special conditions and the risks
they face in fulfilling their daily duties, will be entitled to
all the benefits the law provides.
</P>
<P>
The profession of policeman will be carried out exclusively by
the persons who meet the legal requirements and have the necessary
training provided by graduation from the Interior Ministry's
schools. The new professional titles the Interior Ministry will
grant according to professional qualifications will be police
agent and inspector.
</P>
<P>
The policemen will be forbidden political affiliation and also
barred from holding elective local and central public offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
