<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Leading Markets End Lower By Profit-taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON January 7 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets lost ground
Thursday on a wave of profit-taking despite Asia's rally overnight
and the rate cut in Britain and Demark.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 index closed 0.8 percent lower as
profit-taking and a weak start to New York trading outweighed a 25
basis point cut in UK interest rates.
</P>
<P>
By the close, the index which surged to a near record high
Wednesday had fallen 47.6 points to 6101.2, having been down as
much as 106 points just after Wall Street opened.
</P>
<P>
Bank and telecom stocks which led the upward in the previous
session were the main targets of profit-takers. Abbey National,
NatWest, BT and Cable &AMP; Wireless were among the most notable
fallers in the two sectors.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said leading UK stocks, like their U.S.
counterparts, were ripe for profit-taking after a record liquidity
driven jump on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"After a day like yesterday I expect we'll see a day of
consolidation today," said Paul Nesbitt, a technical strategist in
the City.
</P>
<P>
The market is still positive about earnings ahead of hard
evidence, he said, and "there is nothing to destroy that
expectation".
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt shares tumbled as profit-taking set in after the
hefty gains made earlier in the week. The Dax index closed 120.41
points lower at 5323.21.
</P>
<P>
Traders said investors were cashing in after the buying
euphoria related to the introduction of the euro and the launch of
the London-Frankfurt stock exchange link.
</P>
<P>
Paris shares fell back, hurt also by profit-taking after three
days of strong gains. The Cac 40 finished 64.15 points lower at
4230.67.
</P>
<P>
"It's only normal that the bourse would consolidate a little
after rising around 7 percent in three days," a trader said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
