<HEADLINE> S. Leonean President Reported Safe as Fighting Continues in Free town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Ahmad Tejan
Kabbah was "well and safe" in a military base near the international
airport in capital Freetown, a report reaching here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah and members of his family were taken Wednesday by a helicopter to
the military base used by the west African peace-keeping force ECOMOG and
are still there Thursday, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It quoted witnesses as saying that sporadic gunfire continued to rattle
through the city as both sides fought over the central commercial district.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG sources noted that ECOMOG troops had pushed the combined force of
the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) troops and the ex-junta soldiers
back some distance toward the east.
</P>
<P>
But, a witness said that "there have been no major shifts in positions
of both sides" with ECOMOG forces in the west end and the rebels in the
east end.
</P>
<P>
Bodies lay in the streets of the Freetown's rebel-invaded east end
district while a thick pall of smoke was seen rising above east end streets
where the rebels had burnt government and police vehicles, said witnesses.
</P>
<P>
There were few signs of anyone on all the streets in the city early
Thursday except groups of rebels roaming the streets in search of food.
</P>
<P>
A United Nations official was quoted as saying that the rebels were
threatening to attack a key defense force base at Freetown's international
airport in Lungi.
</P>
<P>
Reportedly, rebel commander Sam Bockarie said Wednesday that his men
would only call a halt to the fighting with the ECOMOG troops if detained
rebel leader Foday Sankoh was freed.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh was sentenced to death last October on treason charges after a
coup which overthrew President Kabbah in May 1997. His rebels backed the
military junta that held power until ECOMOG evicted it last February,
reinstating President Kabbah last march. 
</P>
</TEXT>
