<HEADLINE> Mubarak to Visit Syria for Talks on Regional Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
is to pay a visit to Syria Friday for talks with his Syrian
counterpart Hafez al-Assad on regional issues, Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders will discuss the current situation in the Arab
world, the stalled Mideast peace process and ways of advancing the
peace march in particular, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace process came to a halt recently
due to Israel's decision to hold early general elections in May.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations between Syria and Lebanon, on the one hand,
and Israel, on the other, have been in a deadlock since early 1996
due to disputes over the future of the Golan Heights, part of
Syrian territory captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will review the Iraqi issue, the Lockerbie crisis
and other issues affecting the Arab world both politically and
economically, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and al-Assad will examine the "distinguished" bilateral
ties and seek ways of further consolidating the relations in
various domains, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and al-Assad frequently exchange visits in a bid to
coordinate stances on regional issues and international affairs of
mutual concern. 
</P>
