<HEADLINE> Commercial Bank of Ethiopia to Auction Off Debtors' Properties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Commercial Bank of Ethiopia
Thursday announced a plan to auction off the properties pledged by 218
Eritreans and other debtors who owe the bank 46.6 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Vice-President of the Debt
Evaluation and Analysis Department, Mulugeta Gebremedhin, told local press
that 85 percent of the total debt is owed by five huge enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Mulugeta said the remaining 15 percent is owed by individual borrowers.
</P>
<P>
He said the bank has now got legal custody of 90 percent of the various
properties offered as collateral, adding that the properties include
various vehicles, buildings, factories and construction machinery.
</P>
<P>
The official also said over 1.46 million Dollars of the debt owed by the
borrowers has so far been reimbursed, and some of the debtors have
willingly re-payed 8.8 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
He said bid documents for the auction of the five enterprises have been
prepared.
</P>
<P>
Once the government gave the final decision, the auction will go ahead,
he added. 
