<HEADLINE> Lesotho to Hold Int'l Seminar on Protecting Ozone Layer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho is to host a four-day
African meeting on protecting the ozone layer, Southern African
Broadcasting Association reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The gathering, organized by Lesotho weather-forecasting department,
will be held in February in Maseru, capital of the mountain kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 21 English-speaking countries in Africa and the United
Nations Environment Program are expected to attend the conference, said the
department.
</P>
<P>
Ts'eliso Sekoli, senior official in Lesotho weather-forecasting
department, was quoted as saying that the meeting would review progress
African countries had made to implement an international agreement to
safeguard the ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
Sekoli said that Lesotho had been chosen to host the meeting because it
was one of nations in Africa effecting the protocol, which was signed in
the Canadian city of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
He said activities which Lesotho had implemented include distributing
equipment capturing ozone-depleting gas from refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
The ozone layer prevents harmful radiation from the sun reaching the
earth. Recent studies show there are holes in the system created by the
use of certain chemicals. 
</P>
