<HEADLINE> (Updates with more details)  U.S. Supreme Court Justice Presides Over Impeachment  Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) - U.S. Supreme Court Justice
William Rehnquist was sworn in Thursday to preside over the
impeachment trial of President Bill Clinton in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The step marks the official opening of the Senate trial in
which the 100-member body will serve as jurors, sworn by Rehnquist
to an oath of impartiality.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in the U.S. since the trial of Andrew
Johnson in 1868 that senators were asked to try a president.
</P>
<P>
Senate President Pro Tempore Strom Thurmond administered the
oath to Chief Justice Rehnquist in which he said: "I solemnly
swear that in all things appertaining to the trial of the
impeachment of President Bill Clinton, now pending, I will do
impartial justice according to the Constitution and laws: So help
me God."
</P>
<P>
Then, Rehnquist, wearing a black robe with gold stripes on the
arms, administered the same oath to all 100 Senate members who
will sit in judgment of the president on two impeachment articles
of perjury and obstruction of justice in the investigation of his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, a White House intern. The
senators signed their names in an oath book.
</P>
<P>
On December 19 last year, the U.S. House of Representatives
passed on largely party-line votes the two articles of impeachment
against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The votes sent the issue to the Senate, where a two-thirds
majority must vote to convict Clinton in order to remove him from
office.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, 13 prosecutors of the House delivered to the
Senate the two articles of impeachment accusing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The ceremonial opening came amid intense, last-minute
bargaining over ground rules.
</P>
<P>
Led by House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, the 13
Republicans named as prosecutors for the trial walked silently
across the Capitol -- followed by cameras that broadcast the scene
live to the nation -- to deliver the papers.
</P>
<P>
Hyde read the two articles of impeachment against Clinton,
passed by the House just three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The crucial question now is whether to allow witnesses, as
demanded by the House but opposed by Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
The White House declared there wasn't a "compelling case" for
ousting Clinton and warned that if Republicans summoned witnesses
"all bets are off" for a speedy resolution of a scandal that has
dominated the country for a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
