<HEADLINE> Clinton to Seek 7-billion-Dollar for Missile Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua)-- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will ask Congress to approve about 7 billion U.S. dollars over the
next six years to develop a limited U.S. defense against ballistic
missiles, New York Times quoted administration officials as saying
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that the funds would be sought next month as
part of the proposed fiscal year 2000 defense budget, but that
Clinton was unlikely to decide on any deployment of the system
until at least June 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon has spent over 50 billion dollars in the past
decade and concentrated -- with little success -- on developing
anti-missile systems that might protect U.S. troops and specific
targets from attack.
</P>
<P>
The effort has been burdened by technological and other
problems, including five successive test failures of the proposed
theater high-altitude missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
On January 2, Clinton announced that he will seek an additional
12 billion dollars in overall defense spending for the year 2000
as part of a 110 billion dollars boost for the Pentagon between
then and the year 2005. 
</P>
