<HEADLINE> U.S. Jobless Number Falls to 350,000 Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of applications
for unemployment benefits fell by 22,000 last week to a seasonally
adjusted 350,000, the U.S. Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Department said that this number recovered from the week
before when claims recorded the worst increase in six years.
</P>
<P>
The claims had hit an eight-month low of 289,000 during the
week ended Dec. 19, but during Christmas week shot up by 83,000,
the biggest increase since July 1992. Reports from states
suggested that weather including flooding in the Northwest
contributed to the big jump.
</P>
<P>
Economists have been scrutinizing jobless claims for signs that
the global economic slump is impairing U.S. workers. But they
cautioned against reading too much into the volatile weekly
figures until a clear trend has been established.
</P>
<P>
Continuing claims for unemployment insurance rose last week by
121,000 to 2.33 million, also the most since last July. 
</P>
