<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Chinese Diplomat Rebutts U.S. House Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese diplomat
rebutted here Thursday U.S. allegations that the satellite launch
cooperation with China had threatened U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
Minister-Counselor He Yafei told a press conference at the
Chinese Embassy that a House panel report on this matter was
"absurd and irresponsible."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House Select Committee issued last week a 700-page
report alleging that American companies had offered "help" for the
improvement of Chinese missile technology when China-made Long
March rockets were used to launch U.S.-made satellites.
</P>
<P>
"This absurd and irresponsible conclusion tarnished the image
of the Long-March rocket, and undermined the international
reputation of its manufacturer and launch services provider. At
the same time, it brought unwarranted damage to normal space
commercial cooperation between China and the United States," said
He, who heads the governmental and congressional section in
the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The House panel report, as indicated by American officials,
covers a 1995 decision by the Commerce Department approving aid
provided by the Hughes Electronics Corporation to Chinese rocket
scientists. Lessons given by the American satellite manufacturer
had broad applications to ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
He refuted the allegation, asserting that China's rocket
technology has attained maturity after four decades of sustained
development and "there is nothing in American rocket technology
that can alarm Chinese space experts."
</P>
<P>
China launched its first satellite, the DFH-1, with a
Long-March 1 rocket and began offering services for international
commercial launches in 1985. "China's overall launch success rate
was comparable to or even better than that of similar launch
vehicles of other providers," He said.
</P>
<P>
"It is entirely within its capacity to investigate and resolve
its launch failures and improve its technology self-reliantly. In
this connection, Chinese space experts have neither asked for any
'tutorial', nor received any help, from anyone outside China,"
He added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese diplomat confirmed that China and the United States
had a smooth cooperation in commercial satellite launch services
in the past two decades. Three relevant agreements including the
Memorandum of Agreement on Satellite Technology Safeguards, were
signed by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, both sides adopted a series of strict control and
security measures including round-the-clock surveillance by
American security personnel of the satellite to be launched,
presence of American officials at all technical coordination
meetings, prior U.S. governmental approval of all data and
information provided to the Chinese side, obtaining an export
license issued by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
"China has always adhered to established international
practices, upheld the principle of fairness and openness and
consistently observed to the letter the three governmental
agreements with the United States. The security of U.S.
technology, consequently, has never been called in question,"
He said.
</P>
<P>
Responding to American suspicion that U.S. normal space
commercial cooperation had facilitated the Chinese to upgrade
their missile technology, He said that the vehicle launch and
missiles launch have major differences, and some people in the
U.S. media and Congress "inadvertently or deliberately, blurred
the distinction between needed and innocuous technical
coordination and illegal divulging of sensitive technologies."
</P>
<P>
"In fact the technical data the Chinese launch vehicle party
asked for from the satellite party has never gone beyond what has
been provided for in the document, which is exactly the same as
asked by the U.S. or any other service providers," the Chinese
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that a normal commercial activity in the
high-tech field serves the national security, political and
economic interests of both countries. It also helps the building
towards a constructive strategic partnership between China and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that there are some people in the United
States who have been attempting to hold back the process of
improving relationship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion of the 20th anniversary of diplomatic relations
between the two countries, President Jiang Zemin and President
Bill Clinton reaffirmed their commitment to seeking closer ties.
But it is believed that ups and downs on the road ahead could
hardly be avoided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990108.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-07 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
