<HEADLINE> British Military Exercises not Allowed in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The government of Cyprus
Thursday said it would not allow Britain to conduct military
exercises in Akamas, an environmentally unique place in the
western tip of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Government Spokesman Christos Stylianides said in a daily
briefing that negotiations are underway for an alternative site.
</P>
<P>
The British forces in Cyprus are allowed, under the 1960 Treaty
of Establishment, to conduct military exercises in Cyprus each
year.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the government's position on the issue shows
its respect for the 1960 Treaty of Establishment.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus Foreign Ministry has succeeded in reducing the
number of troops that will participate in the exercises, scheduled
for Friday.
</P>
<P>
Both local and international environmental organizations are
strongly opposed to the war games in the region and have stepped
up their efforts to make Akamas a national park. 
</P>
