<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Administrative Reforms Kick Off in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese government Thursday
decided to abolish or merge a number of public institutions,
signalling the administrative reform that it promised earlier to
parliament kicked off.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a weekly cabinet session presided by
President Emile Lahoud Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Information Minister Anwar Khalil said
the state-run telephone company OGERO will be replaced by Lebanon
Telecom, an institute with sweeping powers, including the
establishment, equipping, investment and maintenance of the
telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
Six public departments, including National Institution for
Statistical Services and Studies, Institution for Guranteeing
Lebanese Exports, that existed only on paper, will be closed,
Khalil said.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also decided to merge the Council for Executing
Construction Projects with the Council for Executing Grand
Projects in Beirut. And the 22 Water Authorities will be reduced
to five.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Development and Reconstruction, a governmental
body which spearheads Lebanon's post-war reconstruction drive
launched by former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, is to be
reorganized, Khalik said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the streamlining move was aimed at
improving public bodies' efficiency and reducing public
expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's new government was formed by veteran politician and
economist Salim Hoss last December after his predecessor Hariri
refused to remain in office.
</P>
<P>
In his policy statement, Hoss put administrative and economic
reforms as the priorities of his government to bring down the huge
public debts and clean up the corruption-riddled government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
