<HEADLINE> E. African Development Bank Launches New Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- The East African Development Bank (EADB)
 launched here Thursday a new investment instrument in the regional money
market in a bid to help mobilize local investment resources.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Medium Term Note (MTN) issue worth 1.2 billion Shillings
(200 million U.S. Dollars) will have a maximum issue period of 18 months
and will be traded in the secondary market of the Nairobi Stock Exchange,
the bank announced.
</P>
<P>
It will be initially on offer in Kenya and Uganda and later in Tanzania,
said the bank's Director General, Fabian Tibeita.
</P>
<P>
He said that the bank had already secured the approval of the Capital
Markets Authority to trade in the paper.
</P>
<P>
The MTN will have a maturity period of one to five years and bids from
the investing public can be placed with the arrangers, the dealers or the
placing agent.
</P>
<P>
With a term of four years, the notes will be redeemable in eight equal
semi-annual payments and will be issued in denominations of one million
Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The floating rate coupon rate for the first interest payment (for the
period from January 15, 1999 to July 15) has been fixed at 19.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
The debt instrument will be on sale at the NSE from January 15 at a
purchase price of 99.75 percent and its final maturity date will be
January 15, 2003.
</P>
<P>
The bank is one of the few surviving relics of the East African
Community that was dismissed in 1977.
</P>
<P>
The bank now is owned by the three member states of the East African
Cooperation -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
