<HEADLINE> Kenyan Coffee Production Drops Further in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 7 (Xinhua) -- Coffee yield in Kenya declined in 1998
for a third running year, according to a report available here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Mild Coffee Trade Association F. J. Mwangi was quoted as
saying that the country's coffee output went down from 97,575 tons
between 1995-1996 to 53,000 tons from 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
The fall in coffee production, Mwangi said, was attributed to adverse
weather conditions such as the prolonged drought in early 1997 followed by
the massive destruction caused by the El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
The poor weather resulted in the production of smaller beans mainly in
the major crop growing areas, he noted at a recent general meeting of the
association.
</P>
<P>
"This had a negative effect for high altitude areas but was beneficial
to low altitude areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he added Kenya's coffee continued to do well in the
international market due to its high quality despite of a drop of prices in
 the world market since last July when Latin America saw a bumper harvest.
</P>
</TEXT>
