<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 21:10 GMT, January 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian incumbent President Hafez Assad has been
nominated for a fifth seven-year term in office, a statement faxed
to Xinhua said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced Thursday by Assistant Secretary
General of the ruling Arab Socialist Baathist Party (ASBP)
Sulaiman Kaddah.
</P>
<P>
Kaddah said the leadership of the ASBP met Wednesday and
unanimously renominated Assad as the next president, whose current
tenure will expire on March 12, 1999. (BC-Syria-Presidential Nomination)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami vowed to sack
Intelligence Minister Qorbanali Dorri Najafabadi after his
ministry admitted that its agents were involved in serial murders
of dissidents and intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
"President Khatami underlined that he would dismiss him
(Najafabadi) if he would not resign," local daily Salam on
Thursday quoted informed sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Khatami would take over the Intelligence
Ministry by himself and appoint one of the current deputy
intelligence ministers as acting intelligence minister.
(BC-Iran-Intelligence Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Democratic Left Party (DSP) leader Bulent
Ecevit Thursday said that President Suleyman Demirel had again
authorized him to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit, also deputy prime minister of the ousted government
led by Motherland Party (ANAP) Chairman Mesut Yilmaz, made the
announcement after his one-hour-long meeting with Demirel at the
presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
(BC-Turkey-Government)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The ruling Likud party announced Thursday its
campaign strategies which focus on the difference of its goals
and policies with those of the opposition Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, head of Likud steering
committee for the upcoming elections, disclosed some of the new
Likud strategies which include sharp criticism of the Labor
Party, Israel Radio reported, without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Labor legislator and former prime minister
Shimon Peres declared his support for Labor leader Ehud Barak,
with whom he has different views on many issues.
(BC-Israel-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq has signed 42 oil contracts since the fifth
phase of the U.N. oil-for-food program started on November 26 last
year, said Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Economist weekly, Rashid said 30
contracts have got approval from the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was put under the U.N. sanctions after its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990, but in 1996 the U.N. hammered out an oil-for-food
program allowing Iraq to export a limited amount of oil to buy
food and medicine. (BC-Iraq-Oil Minister) 
</P>
</TEXT>
