<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Rise in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 7(Xinhua) -- The U.S. Commerce Department
said Thursday that new orders to factories rose 0.6 percent in
November to a seasonally adjusted 337 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
It said this was the fifth increase in six months, showing the
U.S. economy was winding up 1998 on a strong note. For the first
11 months of the year, factory orders were 2 percent higher than
the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
For much of the year, strong gains for computers,
communications equipment and autos have helped offset a drop in
orders to steel mills and a lackluster increase at aircraft
plants, owing to the global economic crisis that began in Asia in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Orders for big-ticket durable goods rose 0.8 percent in
November. They were led by a 9.2 percent rebound in orders for
primary metals such as steel, the first gain in the sector since
August and the strongest in more than four years. Orders for
nondurable goods also rose 0.3 percent, with an increase for
chemical products offsetting a decline in textiles.
</P>
<P>
Economists said orders are a key barometer of future factory
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
